# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: topology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:topology/compact-space] In mathematics, especially general topology and mathematical analysis, **compactness** is a property of a space that makes it behave in many ways like a finite set.
[src:topology/compact-space] For instance, on a finite set every infinite sequence must take some value infinitely often, by the pigeonhole principle.
[src:topology/compact-space] For subsets of Euclidean space, the analogous statement is sequential compactness: a set is compact if and only if every infinite sequence in the set has a subsequence that converges to a point of the set.
[src:topology/compact-space] Likewise, whereas every real-valued function on a finite set is bounded and attains its maximum and minimum, every continuous real-valued function on a compact space has these properties.
[src:topology/compact-space] For compact subsets of Euclidean space, this is the extreme value theorem.
[src:topology/compact-space] Another basic property of finite sets is that every cover of a finite set by subsets has a finite subcover: one may choose, for each point of the finite set, a member of the cover containing it.
[src:topology/compact-space] The corresponding topological property is used to define compactness: a topological space is compact if every open cover has a finite subcover.
[src:topology/compact-space] In metric spaces this is equivalent to several other formulations, including sequential compactness, though these equivalences can fail in more general topological spaces.
[src:topology/compact-space] Thus every sequence in the closed unit interval [0,1] has a convergent subsequence with limit in [0,1], whereas this fails for spaces such as the open interval (0,1) and the real line.
[src:topology/compact-space] For subsets of Euclidean space, compactness is equivalent to being closed and bounded, by the Heine–Borel theorem.
[src:topology/compact-space] The property of compactness often allows local information to be combined into global conclusions.
[src:topology/compact-space] The term **compact set** may refer either to a compact topological space or, more commonly, to a subset of a topological space that is compact in the subspace topology.
[src:topology/compact-space] Compactness was formally introduced by Maurice Fréchet in 1906 in work generalizing the Bolzano–Weierstrass theorem from sets of points to spaces of functions.
[src:topology/compact-space] Later, Pavel Alexandrov and Pavel Urysohn developed the open-cover formulation that is now standard in topology.
[src:topology/compact-space] Compactness plays a central role throughout mathematics; for example, continuous real-valued functions on compact spaces attain maxima and minima, and major results such as the Arzelà–Ascoli theorem and the Peano existence theorem depend on compactness.
[src:topology/compact-space] In the 19th century, several disparate mathematical properties were understood that would later be seen as consequences of compactness.
[src:topology/compact-space] On the one hand, Bernard Bolzano (1817) had been aware that any bounded sequence of points (in the line or plane, for instance) has a subsequence that must eventually get arbitrarily close to some other point, called a limit point.
[src:topology/compact-space] Bolzano's proof relied on the method of bisection: the sequence was placed into an interval that was then divided into two equal parts, and a part containing infinitely many terms of the sequence was selected.
[src:topology/compact-space] The process could then be repeated by dividing the resulting smaller interval into smaller and smaller parts—until it closes down on the desired limit point.
[src:topology/compact-space] The full significance of Bolzano's theorem, and its method of proof, would not emerge until almost 50 years later when it was rediscovered by Karl Weierstrass.
[src:topology/compact-space] In the 1880s, it became clear that results similar to the Bolzano–Weierstrass theorem could be formulated for spaces of functions rather than just numbers or geometrical points.
[src:topology/compact-space] The idea of regarding functions as themselves points of a generalized space dates back to the investigations of Giulio Ascoli and Cesare Arzelà.
[src:topology/compact-space] The uniform limit of this sequence then played precisely the same role as Bolzano's "limit point".
[src:topology/compact-space] Towards the beginning of the twentieth century, results similar to that of Arzelà and Ascoli began to accumulate in the area of integral equations, as investigated by David Hilbert and Erhard Schmidt.
[src:topology/compact-space] For a certain class of Green's functions coming from solutions of integral equations, Schmidt had shown that a property analogous to the Arzelà–Ascoli theorem held in the sense of mean convergence – or convergence in what would later be dubbed a Hilbert space.
[src:topology/compact-space] This ultimately led to the notion of a compact operator as an offshoot of the general notion of a compact space.
[src:topology/compact-space] It was Maurice Fréchet who, in 1906, had distilled the essence of the Bolzano–Weierstrass property and coined the term *compactness* to refer to this general phenomenon (he used the term already in his 1904 paper which led to the famous 1906 thesis).
[src:topology/compact-space] However, a different notion of compactness altogether had also slowly emerged at the end of the 19th century from the study of the continuum, which was seen as fundamental for the rigorous formulation of analysis.
[src:topology/compact-space] In 1870, Eduard Heine showed that a continuous function defined on a closed and bounded interval was in fact uniformly continuous.
[src:topology/compact-space] In the course of the proof, he made use of a lemma that from any countable cover of the interval by smaller open intervals, it was possible to select a finite number of these that also covered it.
[src:topology/compact-space] The significance of this lemma was recognized by Émile Borel (1895), and it was generalized to arbitrary collections of intervals by Pierre Cousin (1895) and Henri Lebesgue (1904).
[src:topology/compact-space] The Heine–Borel theorem, as the result is now known, is another special property possessed by closed and bounded sets of real numbers.
[src:topology/compact-space] This property was significant because it allowed for the passage from local information about a set (such as the continuity of a function) to global information about the set (such as the uniform continuity of a function).
[src:topology/compact-space] This sentiment was expressed by Lebesgue (1904), who also exploited it in the development of the integral now bearing his name.
[src:topology/compact-space] Ultimately, the Russian school of point-set topology, under the direction of Pavel Alexandrov and Pavel Urysohn, formulated Heine–Borel compactness in a way that could be applied to the modern notion of a topological space.
[src:topology/compact-space] Alexandrov & Urysohn (1929) showed that the earlier version of compactness due to Fréchet, now called (relative) sequential compactness, under appropriate conditions followed from the version of compactness that was formulated in terms of the existence of finite subcovers.
[src:topology/compact-space] It was this notion of compactness that became the dominant one, because it was not only a stronger property, but it could be formulated in a more general setting with a minimum of additional technical machinery, as it relied only on the structure of the open sets in a space.
[src:topology/compact-space] Any finite space is compact; a finite subcover can be obtained by selecting, for each point, an open set containing it.
[src:topology/compact-space] A nontrivial example of a compact space is the (closed) unit interval [0,1] of real numbers.
[src:topology/compact-space] If one chooses an infinite number of distinct points in the unit interval, then there must be some accumulation point among these points in that interval.
[src:topology/compact-space] For instance, the odd-numbered terms of the sequence 1, ⁠1/2⁠, ⁠1/3⁠, ⁠3/4⁠, ⁠1/5⁠, ⁠5/6⁠, ⁠1/7⁠, ⁠7/8⁠, ... get arbitrarily close to 0, while the even-numbered ones get arbitrarily close to 1.
[src:topology/compact-space] The given example sequence shows the importance of including the boundary points of the interval, since the limit points must be in the space itself—an open (or half-open) interval of the real numbers is not compact.
[src:topology/compact-space] It is also crucial that the interval be bounded, since in the interval [0,∞), one could choose the sequence of points 0, 1, 2, 3, ..., of which no sub-sequence ultimately gets arbitrarily close to any given real number.
[src:topology/compact-space] In two dimensions, closed disks are compact since for any infinite number of points sampled from a disk, some subset of those points must get arbitrarily close either to a point within the disc, or to a point on the boundary.
[src:topology/compact-space] Likewise, a circle in the plane is compact (easily seen by its being closed and bounded).
[src:topology/compact-space] However, an open disk is not compact, because a sequence of points can tend to the boundary—without getting arbitrarily close to any point in the interior.
[src:topology/compact-space] Likewise, spheres are compact, but a sphere missing a point is not since a sequence of points can still tend to the missing point, thereby not getting arbitrarily close to any point *within* the space.
[src:topology/compact-space] Lines and planes are not compact, since one can take a set of equally-spaced points in any given direction without approaching any point.
[src:topology/compact-space] Various definitions of compactness may apply, depending on the level of generality.
[src:topology/compact-space] A subset of Euclidean space in particular is compact if and only if it is closed and bounded.
[src:topology/compact-space] This implies, by the Bolzano–Weierstrass theorem, that any infinite sequence from the set has a subsequence that converges to a point in the set.
[src:topology/compact-space] Various equivalent notions of compactness, such as sequential compactness and limit point compactness, can be developed in general metric spaces.
[src:topology/compact-space] In contrast, the different notions of compactness are not equivalent in general topological spaces, and the most useful notion of compactness—originally called *bicompactness*—is defined using covers consisting of open sets (see *Open cover definition* below).
[src:topology/compact-space] That this form of compactness holds for closed and bounded subsets of Euclidean space is known as the Heine–Borel theorem.
[src:topology/compact-space] Compactness, when defined in this manner, often allows one to take information that is known locally—in a neighbourhood of each point of the space—and to extend it to information that holds globally throughout the space.
[src:topology/compact-space] An example of this phenomenon is Dirichlet's theorem, to which it was originally applied by Heine, that a continuous function on a compact interval is uniformly continuous; here, continuity is a local property of the function, and uniform continuity the corresponding global property.
[src:topology/compact-space] Formally, a topological space X is called *compact* if every open cover of X has a finite subcover.
[src:topology/compact-space] Some branches of mathematics such as algebraic geometry, typically influenced by the French school of Bourbaki, use the term *quasi-compact* for the general notion, and reserve the term *compact* for topological spaces that are both Hausdorff and *quasi-compact*.
[src:topology/compact-space] A compact set is sometimes referred to as a *compactum*, plural *compacta*.
[src:topology/compact-space] Equivalently, K is compact as a subset of X if and only if the topological space K is compact in the subspace topology.
[src:topology/compact-space] In particular, if $K\subset Y\subset X$ , with subset Y equipped with the subspace topology, then K is compact in Y if and only if K is compact in X.
[src:topology/compact-space] Furthermore, the compactness of K as a subset of a topological space X is independent of the embedding, provided that the subspace topology on K is the same.
[src:topology/compact-space] X has a sub-base such that every cover of the space, by members of the sub-base, has a finite subcover (Alexander's sub-base theorem).
[src:topology/compact-space] Any collection of closed subsets of X with the finite intersection property has nonempty intersection.
[src:topology/compact-space] Every net on X has a convergent subnet (see the article on nets for a proof).
[src:topology/compact-space] Every filter on X has a convergent refinement.
[src:topology/compact-space] Every ultrafilter on X converges to at least one point.
[src:topology/compact-space] Every infinite subset of X has a complete accumulation point.
[src:topology/compact-space] For every topological space Y, the projection $X\times Y\to Y$ is a closed mapping (see proper map).
[src:topology/compact-space] Every open cover linearly ordered by subset inclusion contains X.
[src:topology/compact-space] Bourbaki defines a compact space (quasi-compact space) as a topological space where each filter has a cluster point (i.e., 8. in the above).
[src:topology/compact-space] For any subset A of Euclidean space, A is compact if and only if it is closed and bounded; this is the Heine–Borel theorem.
[src:topology/compact-space] As a Euclidean space is a metric space, the conditions in the next subsection also apply to all of its subsets.
[src:topology/compact-space] Of all of the equivalent conditions, it is in practice easiest to verify that a subset is closed and bounded, for example, for a closed interval or closed n-ball.
[src:topology/compact-space] (*X*, *d*) is complete and totally bounded (this is also equivalent to compactness for uniform spaces).
[src:topology/compact-space] (*X*, *d*) is sequentially compact; that is, every sequence in X has a convergent subsequence whose limit is in X (this is also equivalent to compactness for first-countable uniform spaces).
[src:topology/compact-space] (*X*, *d*) is limit point compact (also called weakly countably compact); that is, every infinite subset of X has at least one limit point in X.
[src:topology/compact-space] (*X*, *d*) is countably compact; that is, every countable open cover of X has a finite subcover.
[src:topology/compact-space] X is empty or (*X*, *d*) is the image of a continuous function from the Cantor set.
[src:topology/compact-space] Every decreasing nested sequence of nonempty closed subsets *S*1 ⊇ *S*2 ⊇ ... in (*X*, *d*) has a nonempty intersection.
[src:topology/compact-space] Every increasing nested sequence of proper open subsets *S*1 ⊆ *S*2 ⊆ ... in (*X*, *d*) fails to cover X.
[src:topology/compact-space] (*X*, *d*) is second-countable, separable and Lindelöf – these three conditions are equivalent for metric spaces.
[src:topology/compact-space] The converse is not true; e.g., a countable discrete space satisfies these three conditions, but is not compact.
[src:topology/compact-space] X is closed and bounded (as a subset of any metric space whose restricted metric is d).
[src:topology/compact-space] The converse may fail for a non-Euclidean space; e.g. the real line equipped with the discrete metric is closed and bounded but not compact, as the collection of all singletons of the space is an open cover which admits no finite subcover.
[src:topology/compact-space] Every subset of X has a supremum (i.e. a least upper bound) in X.
[src:topology/compact-space] Every subset of X has an infimum (i.e. a greatest lower bound) in X.
[src:topology/compact-space] Every nonempty closed subset of X has a maximum and a minimum element.
[src:topology/compact-space] An ordered space satisfying (any one of) these conditions is called a complete lattice.
[src:topology/compact-space] Every monotone increasing sequence in X converges to a unique limit in X.
[src:topology/compact-space] Every monotone decreasing sequence in X converges to a unique limit in X.
[src:topology/compact-space] Every decreasing nested sequence of nonempty closed subsets S1 ⊇ S2 ⊇ ... in (*X*, <) has a nonempty intersection.
[src:topology/compact-space] Every increasing nested sequence of proper open subsets S1 ⊆ S2 ⊆ ... in (*X*, <) fails to cover X.
[src:topology/compact-space] Let X be a completely regular Hausdorff space and C(*X*) the ring of real-valued continuous functions on X.
[src:topology/compact-space] For each *p* ∈ *X*, the evaluation map $\operatorname {ev} _{p}\colon C(X)\to \mathbb {R}$ given by $\operatorname {ev} _{p}(f)=f(p)$ is a ring homomorphism.
[src:topology/compact-space] Consequently, X is compact if and only if every maximal ideal of C(*X*) is the kernel of an evaluation homomorphism.
[src:topology/compact-space] If X is not pseudocompact, then C(*X*) has maximal ideals whose residue fields are proper ordered field extensions of $\mathbb {R}$ , often called *hyperreal* fields.
[src:topology/compact-space] In the framework of non-standard analysis, this corresponds to the following characterization of compactness: a topological space X is compact if and only if every point of the natural extension **X* is infinitely close to some point of X (that is, lies in the monad of a point of X).
[src:topology/compact-space] A space X is compact if its hyperreal extension **X* (constructed, for example, by the ultrapower construction) has the property that every point of **X* is infinitely close to some point of *X* ⊂ **X*.
[src:topology/compact-space] For example, an open real interval *X* = (0, 1) is not compact because its hyperreal extension *(0,1) contains infinitesimals, which are infinitely close to 0, which is not a point of X.
[src:topology/compact-space] Since the image of a compact space under a continuous function is compact, the extreme value theorem holds for such spaces: a continuous real-valued function on a nonempty compact space is bounded above and attains its supremum.
[src:topology/compact-space] (Slightly more generally, this is true for an upper semicontinuous function.) As a sort of converse to the above statements, the pre-image of a compact space under a proper map is compact.
[src:topology/compact-space] Every topological space X is an open dense subspace of a compact space having at most one point more than X, by the Alexandroff one-point compactification.
[src:topology/compact-space] By the same construction, every locally compact Hausdorff space X is an open dense subspace of a compact Hausdorff space having at most one point more than X.
[src:topology/compact-space] A nonempty compact subset of the real numbers has a greatest element and a least element.
[src:topology/compact-space] Let X be a totally ordered set endowed with the order topology.
[src:topology/compact-space] Then X is compact if and only if X is a complete lattice (i.e., all subsets have suprema and infima).
[src:topology/connected-space] In topology and related branches of mathematics, a **connected space** is a topological space that cannot be represented as the union of two or more disjoint non-empty open subsets.
[src:topology/connected-space] Connectedness is one of the principal topological properties that distinguish topological spaces.
[src:topology/connected-space] A subset of a topological space X is a *connected set* if it is a connected space when viewed as a subspace of X .
[src:topology/connected-space] Some related but stronger conditions are path connected, simply connected, and n -connected.
[src:topology/connected-space] Another related notion is *locally connected*, which neither implies nor follows from connectedness.
[src:topology/connected-space] A topological space X is said to be *disconnected* if it is the union of two disjoint non-empty open sets.
[src:topology/connected-space] A subset of a topological space is said to be connected if it is connected under its subspace topology.
[src:topology/connected-space] Some authors exclude the empty set (with its unique topology) as a connected space, but this article does not follow that practice.
[src:topology/connected-space] The only subsets of X which are both open and closed (clopen sets) are X and the empty set.
[src:topology/connected-space] The only subsets of X with empty boundary are X and the empty set.
[src:topology/connected-space] X cannot be written as the union of two non-empty separated sets (sets for which each is disjoint from the other's closure).
[src:topology/connected-space] All continuous functions from X to $\{0,1\}$ are constant, where $\{0,1\}$ is the two-point space endowed with the discrete topology.
[src:topology/connected-space] All discrete-valued continuous maps on *X* are constant.
[src:topology/connected-space] Historically this modern formulation of the notion of connectedness (in terms of no partition of X into two separated sets) first appeared (independently) with N.J.
[src:topology/connected-space] Lennes, Frigyes Riesz, and Felix Hausdorff at the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:topology/connected-space] Connectedness defines an equivalence relation in the following sense: given two points $x,y$ in a topological space X , we write $x\sim y$ if $x,y$ belong to the same connected subset.
[src:topology/connected-space] Then this $\sim$ is an equivalence relation.
[src:topology/connected-space] Given some point x in a topological space $X,$ the union of any collection of connected subsets such that each contains x will once again be a connected subset.
[src:topology/connected-space] The components of a topological space X form a partition of X : they are disjoint, non-empty and their union is the whole space.
[src:topology/connected-space] In fact, a connected component is the same as an equivalence class when two points are equivalent if they belong to the same connected subset (see § Formal definition).
[src:topology/connected-space] Every component is a closed subset of the original space.
[src:topology/connected-space] It follows that, in the case where their number is finite, each component is also an open subset.
[src:topology/connected-space] However, if their number is infinite, this might not be the case; for instance, the connected components of the set of the rational numbers are the one-point sets (singletons), which are not open.
[src:topology/connected-space] Proof: Any two distinct rational numbers $q_{1}<q_{2}$ are in different components.
[src:topology/connected-space] Let $\Gamma _{x}$ be the connected component of x in a topological space $X,$ and $\Gamma _{x}'$ be the intersection of all clopen sets containing x (called quasi-component of x ).
[src:topology/connected-space] Then $\Gamma _{x}\subset \Gamma '_{x}$ where the equality holds if X is compact Hausdorff or locally connected.
[src:topology/connected-space] A space in which all components are one-point sets is called *totally disconnected*.
[src:topology/connected-space] Related to this property, a space X is called *totally separated* if, for any two distinct elements x and y of X , there exist disjoint open sets U containing x and V containing y such that X is the union of U and V .
[src:topology/connected-space] Clearly, any totally separated space is totally disconnected, but the converse does not hold.
[src:topology/connected-space] For example, take two copies of the rational numbers $\mathbb {Q}$ , and identify them at every point except zero.
[src:topology/connected-space] The resulting space, with the quotient topology, is totally disconnected.
[src:topology/connected-space] However, by considering the two copies of zero, one sees that the space is not totally separated.
[src:topology/connected-space] In fact, it is not even Hausdorff, and the condition of being totally separated is strictly stronger than the condition of being Hausdorff.
[src:topology/connected-space] Every finitely generated projective module over R has constant rank.
[src:topology/connected-space] R has no idempotent $\neq 0,1$ (i.e., R is not a product of two rings in a nontrivial way).
[src:topology/connected-space] An example of a space that is not connected is a plane with an infinite line deleted from it.
[src:topology/connected-space] Other examples of disconnected spaces (that is, spaces which are not connected) include the plane with an annulus removed, as well as the union of two disjoint closed disks, where all examples of this paragraph bear the subspace topology induced by two-dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:topology/connected-space] A *path-connected space* is a stronger notion of connectedness, requiring the structure of a path.
[src:topology/connected-space] A *path* from a point x to a point y in a topological space X is a continuous function f from the unit interval $[0,1]$ to X with $f(0)=x$ and $f(1)=y$ .
[src:topology/connected-space] A *path-component* of X is an equivalence class of X under the equivalence relation which makes x equivalent to y if and only if there is a path from x to y .
[src:topology/connected-space] The space X is said to be *path-connected* (or *pathwise connected* or $\mathbf {0}$ *-connected*) if there is exactly one path-component.
[src:topology/connected-space] Equivalently, a path-component of X is a maximal path-connected subset of X (to see the equivalence, note a path-component in the previous sense is path-connected).
[src:topology/connected-space] Every path-connected space is connected.
[src:topology/connected-space] The converse is not always true: examples of connected spaces that are not path-connected include the extended long line $L^{*}$ and the topologist's sine curve.
[src:topology/connected-space] Subsets of the real line $\mathbb {R}$ are connected if and only if they are path-connected; these subsets are the intervals and rays of $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:topology/connected-space] Also, open subsets of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ or $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ are connected if and only if they are path-connected.
[src:topology/connected-space] Additionally, connectedness and path-connectedness are the same for finite topological spaces.
[src:topology/connected-space] A space X is said to be *arc-connected* or *arcwise connected* if any two topologically distinguishable points can be joined by an arc, which is an embedding $f:[0,1]\to X$ .
[src:topology/connected-space] An *arc-component* of X is a maximal arc-connected subset of X ; or equivalently an equivalence class of the equivalence relation of whether two points can be joined by an arc or by a path whose points are topologically indistinguishable.
[src:topology/connected-space] Every Hausdorff space that is path-connected is also arc-connected; more generally this is true for a $\Delta$ -Hausdorff space, which is a space where each image of a path is closed.
[src:topology/connected-space] An example of a space which is path-connected but not arc-connected is given by the line with two origins; its two copies of 0 can be connected by a path but not by an arc.
[src:topology/connected-space] Intuition for path-connected spaces does not readily transfer to arc-connected spaces.
[src:topology/connected-space] A topological space is said to be *locally connected* at a point x if every neighbourhood of x contains a connected open neighbourhood.
[src:topology/connected-space] It is *locally connected* if it has a base of connected sets.
[src:topology/connected-space] It can be shown that a space X is locally connected if and only if every component of every open set of X is open.
[src:topology/connected-space] Similarly, a topological space is said to be *locally path-connected* if it has a base of path-connected sets.
[src:topology/connected-space] An open subset of a locally path-connected space is connected if and only if it is path-connected.
[src:topology/connected-space] This generalizes the earlier statement about $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ and $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ , each of which is locally path-connected.
[src:topology/connected-space] More generally, any topological manifold is locally path-connected.
[src:topology/connected-space] Locally connected does not imply connected, nor does locally path-connected imply path connected.
[src:topology/connected-space] A simple example of a locally connected (and locally path-connected) space that is not connected (or path-connected) is the union of two separated intervals in $\mathbb {R}$ , such as $(0,1)\cup (2,3)$ .
[src:topology/connected-space] A classic example of a connected space that is not locally connected is the so-called topologist's sine curve, defined as $T=\{(0,0)\}\cup \left\{\left(x,\sin \left({\tfrac {1}{x}}\right)\right):x\in (0,1]\right\}$ , with the Euclidean topology induced by inclusion in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:topology/connected-space] The intersection of connected sets is not necessarily connected.
[src:topology/connected-space] The union of connected sets is not necessarily connected, as can be seen by considering $X=(0,1)\cup (1,2)$ .
[src:topology/connected-space] Each ellipse is a connected set, but the union is not connected, since it can be partitioned into two disjoint open sets U and V .
[src:topology/connected-space] This means that, if the union X is disconnected, then the collection $\{X_{i}\}$ can be partitioned into two sub-collections, such that the unions of the sub-collections are disjoint and open in X (see picture).
[src:topology/connected-space] This implies that in several cases, a union of connected sets *is* necessarily connected.
[src:topology/connected-space] If the intersection of each pair of sets is not empty ( $\forall i,j:X_{i}\cap X_{j}\neq \emptyset$ ) then again they cannot be partitioned to collections with disjoint unions, so their union must be connected.
[src:topology/connected-space] If the sets can be ordered as a "linked chain", i.e. indexed by integer indices and $\forall i:X_{i}\cap X_{i+1}\neq \emptyset$ , then again their union must be connected.
[src:topology/connected-space] If the sets are pairwise-disjoint and the quotient space $X/\{X_{i}\}$ is connected, then X must be connected.
[src:topology/connected-space] Otherwise, if $U\cup V$ is a separation of X then $q(U)\cup q(V)$ is a separation of the quotient space (since $q(U),q(V)$ are disjoint and open in the quotient space).
[src:topology/connected-space] The set difference of connected sets is not necessarily connected.
[src:topology/connected-space] However, if $X\supseteq Y$ and their difference $X\setminus Y$ is disconnected (and thus can be written as a union of two open sets $X_{1}$ and $X_{2}$ ), then the union of Y with each such component is connected (i.e. $Y\cup X_{i}$ is connected for all i ).
[src:topology/connected-space] By contradiction, suppose $Y\cup X_{1}$ is not connected.
[src:topology/connected-space] So it can be written as the union of two disjoint open sets, e.g. $Y\cup X_{1}=Z_{1}\cup Z_{2}$ .
[src:topology/connected-space] Because Y is connected, it must be entirely contained in one of these components, say $Z_{1}$ , and thus $Z_{2}$ is contained in $X_{1}$ .
[src:topology/connected-space] Now we know that: $X=\left(Y\cup X_{1}\right)\cup X_{2}=\left(Z_{1}\cup Z_{2}\right)\cup X_{2}=\left(Z_{1}\cup X_{2}\right)\cup \left(Z_{2}\cap X_{1}\right)$ The two sets in the last union are disjoint and open in X , so there is a separation of X , contradicting the fact that X is connected.
[src:topology/connected-space] Graphs have path connected subsets, namely those subsets for which every pair of points has a path of edges joining them.
[src:topology/connected-space] However, it is not always possible to find a topology on the set of points which induces the same connected sets.
[src:topology/connected-space] The 5-cycle graph (and any n -cycle with $n>3$ odd) is one such example.
[src:topology/connected-space] As a consequence, a notion of connectedness can be formulated independently of the topology on a space.
[src:topology/connected-space] To wit, there is a category of connective spaces consisting of sets with collections of connected subsets satisfying connectivity axioms; their morphisms are those functions which map connected sets to connected sets (Muscat & Buhagiar 2006).
[src:topology/connected-space] Topological spaces and graphs are special cases of connective spaces; indeed, the finite connective spaces are precisely the finite graphs.
[src:topology/connected-space] However, every graph can be canonically made into a topological space, by treating vertices as points and edges as copies of the unit interval (see topological graph theory#Graphs as topological spaces).
[src:topology/connected-space] Then one can show that the graph is connected (in the graph theoretical sense) if and only if it is connected as a topological space.
[src:topology/connected-space] In general, any path connected space must be connected but there exist connected spaces that are not path connected.
[src:topology/connected-space] The deleted comb space furnishes such an example, as does the above-mentioned topologist's sine curve.
[src:topology/connected-space] A well-chained space is a metric space in which two arbitrary points can be connected by a chain of points that are arbitrarily close.
[src:topology/connected-space] While any well-chained set X is connected, the converse isn't true (an example being $\mathbb {Q}$ ).
[src:topology/continuous-function] In mathematics, a **continuous function** is a function such that a small variation of the argument induces a small variation of the value of the function.
[src:topology/continuous-function] This implies there are no abrupt changes in value, known as *discontinuities*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] More precisely, a function is continuous if arbitrarily small changes in its value can be assured by restricting to sufficiently small changes of its argument.
[src:topology/continuous-function] A **discontinuous function** is a function that is *not continuous*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Until the 19th century, mathematicians largely relied on intuitive notions of continuity and considered only continuous functions.
[src:topology/continuous-function] The epsilon–delta definition of a limit was introduced to formalize the definition of continuity.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Continuity is one of the core concepts of calculus and mathematical analysis, where arguments and values of functions are real and complex numbers.
[src:topology/continuous-function] The concept has been generalized to functions between metric spaces and between topological spaces.
[src:topology/continuous-function] The latter are the most general continuous functions, and their definition is the basis of topology.
[src:topology/continuous-function] A stronger form of continuity is uniform continuity.
[src:topology/continuous-function] In order theory, especially in domain theory, a related concept of continuity is Scott continuity.
[src:topology/continuous-function] As a practical example, the function *H*(*t*) denoting the height of a growing flower at time t would be considered continuous.
[src:topology/continuous-function] In contrast, the function *M*(*t*) denoting the amount of money in a bank account at time t would be considered discontinuous since it "jumps" at each point in time when money is deposited or withdrawn.
[src:topology/continuous-function] A form of the epsilon–delta definition of continuity was first given by Bernard Bolzano in 1817.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Augustin-Louis Cauchy defined continuity of $y=f(x)$ as follows: an infinitely small increment $\alpha$ of the independent variable x always produces an infinitely small change $f(x+\alpha )-f(x)$ of the dependent variable y (see e.g.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Cauchy defined infinitely small quantities in terms of variable quantities, and his definition of continuity closely parallels the infinitesimal definition used today (see microcontinuity).
[src:topology/continuous-function] The formal definitions for, and distinction between, pointwise continuity and uniform continuity were first given by Bolzano in the 1830s, but the work wasn't published until the 1930s.
[src:topology/continuous-function] All three of these nonequivalent definitions of pointwise continuity are still in use.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Eduard Heine provided the first published definition of uniform continuity in 1872, but based these ideas on lectures given by Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet in 1854.
[src:topology/continuous-function] A real function, that is, a function from real numbers to real numbers, can be represented by a graph in the Cartesian plane; such a function is continuous if, roughly speaking, the graph is a single unbroken curve whose domain is the entire real line.
[src:topology/continuous-function] A more mathematically rigorous definition is given below.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Continuity of real functions is usually defined in terms of limits.
[src:topology/continuous-function] There are several different definitions of the (global) continuity of a function, which depend on the nature of its domain.
[src:topology/continuous-function] A function is continuous on an open interval if the interval is contained in the function's domain and the function is continuous at every point in the interval.
[src:topology/continuous-function] A function that is continuous on the interval $(-\infty ,+\infty )$ (the whole real line) is often simply called a continuous function; one also says that such a function is *continuous everywhere*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] For example, all polynomial functions are continuous everywhere.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Many commonly encountered functions are partial functions that have a domain formed by all real numbers, except for some isolated points.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Examples include the reciprocal function ${\textstyle x\mapsto {\frac {1}{x}}}$ and the tangent function $x\mapsto \tan x.$ When they are continuous on their domain, one says, in some contexts, that they are continuous, although they are not continuous everywhere.
[src:topology/continuous-function] In other contexts, mainly when one is interested in their behavior near the exceptional points, one says they are discontinuous.
[src:topology/continuous-function] A partial function is *discontinuous* at a point if the point belongs to the topological closure of its domain, and either the point does not belong to the domain of the function or the function is not continuous at the point.
[src:topology/continuous-function] For example, the functions ${\textstyle x\mapsto {\frac {1}{x}}}$ and ${\textstyle x\mapsto \sin({\frac {1}{x}})}$ are discontinuous at 0, and remain discontinuous whichever value is chosen for defining them at 0.
[src:topology/continuous-function] A point where a function is discontinuous is called a *discontinuity*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Using mathematical notation, several ways exist to define continuous functions in the three senses mentioned above.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Let ${\textstyle f:D\to \mathbb {R} }$ be a function whose domain D is contained in $\mathbb {R}$ of real numbers.
[src:topology/continuous-function] In the case of an open interval, a and b do not belong to D , and the values $f(a)$ and $f(b)$ are not defined, and if they are, they do not matter for continuity on D .
[src:topology/continuous-function] Second, the limit of that equation has to exist.
[src:topology/continuous-function] A neighborhood of a point *c* is a set that contains, at least, all points within some fixed distance of *c*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Intuitively, a function is continuous at a point *c* if the range of *f* over the neighborhood of *c* shrinks to a single point $f(c)$ as the width of the neighborhood around *c* shrinks to zero.
[src:topology/continuous-function] As neighborhoods are defined in any topological space, this definition of a continuous function applies not only for real functions but also when the domain and the codomain are topological spaces and is thus the most general definition.
[src:topology/continuous-function] It follows that a function is automatically continuous at every isolated point of its domain.
[src:topology/continuous-function] For example, every real-valued function on the integers is continuous.
[src:topology/continuous-function] In modern terms, this is generalized by the definition of continuity of a function with respect to a basis for the topology, here the metric topology.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Weierstrass had required that the interval $x_{0}-\delta <x<x_{0}+\delta$ be entirely within the domain D , but Jordan removed that restriction.
[src:topology/continuous-function] In proofs and numerical analysis, we often need to know how fast limits are converging, or in other words, control of the remainder.
[src:topology/continuous-function] We can formalize this to a definition of continuity.
[src:topology/continuous-function] A function is continuous in $x_{0}$ if it is *C*-continuous for some control function *C*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] This approach leads naturally to refining the notion of continuity by restricting the set of admissible control functions.
[src:topology/continuous-function] The oscillation definition can be naturally generalized to maps from a topological space to a metric space.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Cauchy defined the continuity of a function in the following intuitive terms: an infinitesimal change in the independent variable corresponds to an infinitesimal change of the dependent variable (see *Cours d'analyse*, page 34).
[src:topology/continuous-function] Non-standard analysis is a way of making this mathematically rigorous.
[src:topology/continuous-function] The real line is augmented by adding infinite and infinitesimal numbers to form the hyperreal numbers.
[src:topology/continuous-function] In nonstandard analysis, continuity can be defined as follows.
[src:topology/continuous-function] In other words, an infinitesimal increment of the independent variable always produces an infinitesimal change of the dependent variable, giving a modern expression to Augustin-Louis Cauchy's definition of continuity.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Proving the continuity of a function by a direct application of the definition is generally a noneasy task.
[src:topology/continuous-function] These rules imply that every polynomial function is continuous everywhere and that a rational function is continuous everywhere where it is defined, if the numerator and the denominator have no common zeros.
[src:topology/continuous-function] More generally, the quotient of two continuous functions is continuous outside the zeros of the denominator.
[src:topology/continuous-function] An example of a function for which the above rules are not sufficient is the sinc function, which is defined by ⁠ $\operatorname {sinc} (0)=1$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\operatorname {sinc} (x)={\tfrac {\sin x}{x}}$ ⁠ for ⁠ $x\neq 0$ ⁠.
[src:topology/continuous-function] The above rules show immediately that the function is continuous for ⁠ $x\neq 0$ ⁠, but, for proving the continuity at ⁠ 0 ⁠, one has to prove $\lim _{x\to 0}{\frac {\sin x}{x}}=1.$ As this is true, one gets that the sinc function is continuous function on all real numbers.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Then there is no $\delta$ -neighborhood around $x=0$ , i.e. no open interval $(-\delta ,\;\delta )$ with $\delta >0,$ that will force all the $H(x)$ values to be within the $\varepsilon$ -neighborhood of $H(0)$ , i.e. within $(1/2,\;3/2)$ .
[src:topology/continuous-function] Intuitively, we can think of this type of discontinuity as a sudden jump in function values.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Yet another example: the function $f(x)={\begin{cases}\sin \left(x^{-2}\right)&{\text{ if }}x\neq 0\\0&{\text{ if }}x=0\end{cases}}$ is continuous everywhere apart from $x=0$ .
[src:topology/continuous-function] In a similar vein, Dirichlet's function, the indicator function for the set of rational numbers, $D(x)={\begin{cases}0&{\text{ if }}x{\text{ is irrational }}(\in \mathbb {R} \setminus \mathbb {Q} )\\1&{\text{ if }}x{\text{ is rational }}(\in \mathbb {Q} )\end{cases}}$ is nowhere continuous.
[src:topology/continuous-function] For example, if a child grows from 1 m to 1.5 m between the ages of two and six years, then, at some time between two and six years of age, the child's height must have been 1.25 m.
[src:topology/continuous-function] As a consequence, if *f* is continuous on $[a,b]$ and $f(a)$ and $f(b)$ differ in sign, then, at some point $c\in [a,b],$ $f(c)$ must equal zero.
[src:topology/continuous-function] These statements are not, in general, true if the function is defined on an open interval $(a,b)$ (or any set that is not both closed and bounded), as, for example, the continuous function $f(x)={\frac {1}{x}},$ defined on the open interval (0,1), does not attain a maximum, being unbounded above.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Every differentiable function $f:(a,b)\to \mathbb {R}$ is continuous, as can be shown.
[src:topology/continuous-function] However, it is not differentiable at $x=0$ (but is so everywhere else).
[src:topology/continuous-function] Weierstrass's function is also everywhere continuous but nowhere differentiable.
[src:topology/continuous-function] The derivative *f′*(*x*) of a differentiable function *f*(*x*) need not be continuous.
[src:topology/continuous-function] If *f′*(*x*) is continuous, *f*(*x*) is said to be *continuously differentiable*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] In the field of computer graphics, properties related (but not identical) to $C^{0},C^{1},C^{2}$ are sometimes called $G^{0}$ (continuity of position), $G^{1}$ (continuity of tangency), and $G^{2}$ (continuity of curvature); see Smoothness of curves and surfaces.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Every continuous function $f:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R}$ is integrable (for example in the sense of the Riemann integral).
[src:topology/continuous-function] The converse does not hold, as the (integrable but discontinuous) sign function shows.
[src:topology/continuous-function] However, *f* is continuous if all functions $f_{n}$ are continuous and the sequence converges uniformly, by the uniform convergence theorem.
[src:topology/continuous-function] This theorem can be used to show that the exponential functions, logarithms, square root function, and trigonometric functions are continuous.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Discontinuous functions may be discontinuous in a restricted way, giving rise to the concept of directional continuity (or right and left continuous functions) and semi-continuity.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Roughly speaking, a function is *right-continuous* if no jump occurs when the limit point is approached from the right.
[src:topology/continuous-function] This is the same condition as continuous functions, except it is required to hold only for *x* strictly larger than *c*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Requiring $|f(x)-f(c)|<\varepsilon$ to hold instead for all *x* with $c-\delta <x<c$ yields the notion of *left-continuous* functions.
[src:topology/continuous-function] A function is continuous if and only if it is both right-continuous and left-continuous.
[src:topology/continuous-function] A function *f* is *lower semi-continuous* at the point *c* if, roughly, any jumps that might occur only go down, but not up.
[src:topology/continuous-function] That is, for any $\varepsilon >0,$ there exists some number $\delta >0$ such that for all *x* in the domain with $|x-c|<\delta ,$ the value of $f(x)$ satisfies $f(x)\geq f(c)-\varepsilon .$ The reverse condition is *upper semi-continuity*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] The concept of continuous real-valued functions can be generalized to functions between metric spaces.
[src:topology/continuous-function] A metric space is a set X equipped with a function (called metric) $d_{X},$ that can be thought of as a measurement of the distance of any two elements in *X*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Formally, the metric is a function $d_{X}:X\times X\to \mathbb {R}$ that satisfies a number of requirements, notably the triangle inequality.
[src:topology/continuous-function] The set of points at which a function between metric spaces is continuous is a $G_{\delta }$ set – this follows from the $\varepsilon -\delta$ definition of continuity.
[src:topology/continuous-function] This notion of continuity is applied, for example, in functional analysis.
[src:topology/continuous-function] The concept of continuity for functions between metric spaces can be strengthened in various ways by limiting the way $\delta$ depends on $\varepsilon$ and *c* in the definition above.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Intuitively, a function *f* as above is uniformly continuous if the $\delta$ does not depend on the point *c*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] More precisely, it is required that for every real number $\varepsilon >0$ there exists $\delta >0$ such that for every $c,b\in X$ with $d_{X}(b,c)<\delta ,$ we have that $d_{Y}(f(b),f(c))<\varepsilon .$ Thus, any uniformly continuous function is continuous.
[src:topology/continuous-function] The converse does not generally hold but holds when the domain space *X* is compact.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Uniformly continuous maps can be defined in the more general situation of uniform spaces.
[src:topology/continuous-function] A function is Hölder continuous with exponent α (a real number) if there is a constant *K* such that for all $b,c\in X,$ the inequality $d_{Y}(f(b),f(c))\leq K\cdot (d_{X}(b,c))^{\alpha }$ holds.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Any Hölder continuous function is uniformly continuous.
[src:topology/continuous-function] The particular case $\alpha =1$ is referred to as Lipschitz continuity.
[src:topology/continuous-function] That is, a function is Lipschitz continuous if there is a constant *K* such that the inequality $d_{Y}(f(b),f(c))\leq K\cdot d_{X}(b,c)$ holds for any $b,c\in X.$ The Lipschitz condition occurs, for example, in the Picard–Lindelöf theorem concerning the solutions of ordinary differential equations.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Another, more abstract, notion of continuity is the continuity of functions between topological spaces in which there generally is no formal notion of distance, as there is in the case of metric spaces.
[src:topology/continuous-function] The elements of a topology are called open subsets of *X* (with respect to the topology).
[src:topology/continuous-function] A function $f:X\to Y$ between two topological spaces *X* and *Y* is continuous if for every open set $V\subseteq Y,$ the inverse image $f^{-1}(V)=\{x\in X\;|\;f(x)\in V\}$ is an open subset of *X*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] That is, *f* is a function between the sets *X* and *Y* (not on the elements of the topology $T_{X}$ ), but the continuity of *f* depends on the topologies used on *X* and *Y*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] This is equivalent to the condition that the preimages of the closed sets (which are the complements of the open subsets) in *Y* are closed in *X*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] An extreme example: if a set *X* is given the discrete topology (in which every subset is open), all functions $f:X\to T$ to any topological space *T* are continuous.
[src:topology/continuous-function] On the other hand, if *X* is equipped with the indiscrete topology (in which the only open subsets are the empty set and *X*) and the space *T* set is at least T0, then the only continuous functions are the constant functions.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Conversely, any function whose codomain is indiscrete is continuous.
[src:topology/continuous-function] This definition is equivalent to the same statement with neighborhoods restricted to open neighborhoods and can be restated in several ways by using preimages rather than images.
[src:topology/continuous-function] As an open set is a set that is a neighborhood of all its points, a function $f:X\to Y$ is continuous at every point of *X* if and only if it is a continuous function.
[src:topology/continuous-function] If *X* and *Y* are metric spaces, it is equivalent to consider the neighborhood system of open balls centered at *x* and *f*(*x*) instead of all neighborhoods.
[src:topology/continuous-function] This gives back the above $\varepsilon -\delta$ definition of continuity in the context of metric spaces.
[src:topology/continuous-function] In general topological spaces, there is no notion of nearness or distance.
[src:topology/continuous-function] If, however, the target space is a Hausdorff space, it is still true that *f* is continuous at *a* if and only if the limit of *f* as *x* approaches *a* is *f*(*a*).
[src:topology/continuous-function] At an isolated point, every function is continuous.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Several equivalent definitions for a topological structure exist; thus, several equivalent ways exist to define a continuous function.
[src:topology/continuous-function] In several contexts, the topology of a space is conveniently specified in terms of limit points.
[src:topology/continuous-function] This is often accomplished by specifying when a point is the limit of a sequence.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Still, for some spaces that are too large in some sense, one specifies also when a point is the limit of more general sets of points indexed by a directed set, known as nets.
[src:topology/continuous-function] A function is (Heine-)continuous only if it takes limits of sequences to limits of sequences.
[src:topology/continuous-function] In the former case, preservation of limits is also sufficient; in the latter, a function may preserve all limits of sequences yet still fail to be continuous, and preservation of nets is a necessary and sufficient condition.
[src:topology/continuous-function] If X is a first-countable space and countable choice holds, then the converse also holds: any function preserving sequential limits is continuous.
[src:topology/continuous-function] In particular, if X is a metric space, sequential continuity and continuity are equivalent.
[src:topology/continuous-function] For non-first-countable spaces, sequential continuity might be strictly weaker than continuity.
[src:topology/continuous-function] (The spaces for which the two properties are equivalent are called sequential spaces.) This motivates the consideration of nets instead of sequences in general topological spaces.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Continuous functions preserve the limits of nets, and this property characterizes continuous functions.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Assume that $f:A\subseteq \mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R}$ is continuous at $x_{0}$ (in the sense of $\varepsilon -\delta$ continuity).
[src:topology/continuous-function] Instead of specifying topological spaces by their open subsets, any topology on X can alternatively be determined by a closure operator or by an interior operator.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Specifically, the map that sends a subset A of a topological space X to its topological closure $\operatorname {cl} _{X}A$ satisfies the Kuratowski closure axioms.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Similarly, the map that sends a subset A of X to its topological interior $\operatorname {int} _{X}A$ defines an interior operator.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Continuity can also be characterized in terms of filters.
[src:topology/continuous-function] More generally, a continuous function $\left(X,\tau _{X}\right)\to \left(Y,\tau _{Y}\right)$ stays continuous if the topology $\tau _{Y}$ is replaced by a coarser topology and/or $\tau _{X}$ is replaced by a finer topology.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Symmetric to the concept of a continuous map is an open map, for which *images* of open sets are open.
[src:topology/continuous-function] If an open map *f* has an inverse function, that inverse is continuous, and if a continuous map *g* has an inverse, that inverse is open.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Given a bijective function *f* between two topological spaces, the inverse function $f^{-1}$ need not be continuous.
[src:topology/continuous-function] A bijective continuous function with a continuous inverse function is called a *homeomorphism*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] If a continuous bijection has as its domain a compact space and its codomain is Hausdorff, then it is a homeomorphism.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Given a function $f:X\to S,$ where *X* is a topological space and *S* is a set (without a specified topology), the final topology on *S* is defined by letting the open sets of *S* be those subsets *A* of *S* for which $f^{-1}(A)$ is open in *X*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] If *S* has an existing topology, *f* is continuous with respect to this topology if and only if the existing topology is coarser than the final topology on *S*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Thus, the final topology is the finest topology on *S* that makes *f* continuous.
[src:topology/continuous-function] If *f* is surjective, this topology is canonically identified with the quotient topology under the equivalence relation defined by *f*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Dually, for a function *f* from a set *S* to a topological space *X*, the initial topology on *S* is defined by designating as an open set every subset *A* of *S* such that $A=f^{-1}(U)$ for some open subset *U* of *X*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] If *S* has an existing topology, *f* is continuous with respect to this topology if and only if the existing topology is finer than the initial topology on *S*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Thus, the initial topology is the coarsest topology on *S* that makes *f* continuous.
[src:topology/continuous-function] If *f* is injective, this topology is canonically identified with the subspace topology of *S*, viewed as a subset of *X*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] A topology on a set *S* is uniquely determined by the class of all continuous functions $S\to X$ into all topological spaces *X*.
[src:topology/continuous-function] If $f\colon S\to Y$ is a continuous function from some subset S of a topological space X then a *continuous extension* of f to X is any continuous function $F\colon X\to Y$ such that $F(s)=f(s)$ for every $s\in S$ , which is a condition that is often written as $f=F{\big \vert }_{S}$ .
[src:topology/continuous-function] In words, it is any continuous function $F\colon X\to Y$ that restricts to f on S .
[src:topology/continuous-function] This notion is used, for example, in the Tietze extension theorem and the Hahn–Banach theorem.
[src:topology/continuous-function] If $f\colon S\to Y$ is not continuous, then it could not possibly have a continuous extension.
[src:topology/continuous-function] If Y is a Hausdorff space and S is a dense subset of X then a continuous extension of $f\colon S\to Y$ to X , if one exists, will be unique.
[src:topology/continuous-function] Various other mathematical domains use the concept of continuity in different but related meanings.
[src:topology/continuous-function] This notion of continuity is the same as topological continuity when the partially ordered sets are given the Scott topology.
[src:topology/continuous-function] In category theory, a functor $F:{\mathcal {C}}\to {\mathcal {D}}$ between two categories is called *continuous* if it commutes with small limits.
[src:topology/continuous-function] That is to say, $\varprojlim _{i\in I}F(C_{i})\cong F\left(\varprojlim _{i\in I}C_{i}\right)$ for any small (that is, indexed by a set $I,$ as opposed to a class) diagram of objects in ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:topology/continuous-function] A *continuity space* is a generalization of metric spaces and posets, which uses the concept of quantales, and that can be used to unify the notions of metric spaces and domains.
[src:topology/continuous-function] In measure theory, a function $f:E\to \mathbb {R} ^{k}$ defined on a Lebesgue measurable set $E\subseteq \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is called approximately continuous at a point $x_{0}\in E$ if the approximate limit of f at $x_{0}$ exists and equals $f(x_{0})$ .
[src:topology/continuous-function] This generalizes the notion of continuity by replacing the ordinary limit with the approximate limit.
[src:topology/continuous-function] A fundamental result known as the Stepanov-Denjoy theorem states that a function is measurable if and only if it is approximately continuous almost everywhere.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] In the mathematical field of algebraic topology, the **fundamental group** of a topological space is the group of the equivalence classes under homotopy of the loops contained in the space.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] It records information about the basic shape, or holes, of the topological space.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group is the first and simplest homotopy group.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group is a homotopy invariant—topological spaces that are homotopy equivalent (or the stronger case of homeomorphic) have isomorphic fundamental groups.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group of a topological space X is denoted by $\pi _{1}(X)$ .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Start with a space (for example, a surface), and some point in it, and all the loops both starting and ending at this point—paths that start at this point, wander around and eventually return to the starting point.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Two loops can be combined in an obvious way: travel along the first loop, then along the second.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Two loops are considered equivalent if one can be deformed into the other without breaking.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The set of all such loops with this method of combining and this equivalence between them is the fundamental group for that particular space.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Henri Poincaré defined the fundamental group in 1895 in his paper "Analysis situs".
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The concept emerged in the theory of Riemann surfaces, in the work of Bernhard Riemann, Poincaré, and Felix Klein.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] It describes the monodromy properties of complex-valued functions, as well as providing a complete topological classification of closed surfaces.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Throughout this article, X is a topological space.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] A typical example is a surface such as the one depicted at the right.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Moreover, $x_{0}$ is a point in X called the *base-point*.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] (As is explained below, its role is rather auxiliary.) The idea of the definition of the homotopy group is to measure how many (broadly speaking) curves on X can be deformed into each other.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The precise definition depends on the notion of the homotopy of loops, which is explained first.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] such that the starting point $\gamma (0)$ and the end point $\gamma (1)$ are both equal to $x_{0}$ .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] A *homotopy* is a continuous interpolation between two loops.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] If such a homotopy h exists, $\gamma$ and $\gamma '$ are said to be *homotopic*.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The purpose of considering the equivalence classes of loops up to homotopy, as opposed to the set of all loops (the so-called loop space of X ) is that the latter, while being useful for various purposes, is a rather big and unwieldy object.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] By contrast the above quotient is, in many cases, more manageable and computable.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] By the above definition, $\pi _{1}(X,x_{0})$ is just a set.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] It becomes a group (and therefore deserves the name fundamental *group*) using the concatenation of loops.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Thus the loop $\gamma _{0}\cdot \gamma _{1}$ first follows the loop $\gamma _{0}$ with "twice the speed" and then follows $\gamma _{1}$ with "twice the speed".
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The product of two homotopy classes of loops $[\gamma _{0}]$ and $[\gamma _{1}]$ is then defined as $[\gamma _{0}\cdot \gamma _{1}]$ .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] It can be shown that this product does not depend on the choice of representatives and therefore gives a well-defined operation on the set $\pi _{1}(X,x_{0})$ .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] This operation turns $\pi _{1}(X,x_{0})$ into a group.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Its neutral element is the equivalence (homotopy) class of the constant loop, which stays at $x_{0}$ for all times t (i.e. this class consists of all loops that can be continuously deformed into the constant loop; intuitively speaking of all the loops that do not "wrap around a hole").
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The inverse of a (homotopy class of a) loop is the same loop, but traversed in the opposite direction (which is in a different homotopy class).
[src:topology/fundamental-group] is the concatenation of these loops, traversing $\gamma _{0}$ and then $\gamma _{1}$ with quadruple speed, and then $\gamma _{2}$ with double speed.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] traverses the same paths (in the same order), but $\gamma _{0}$ with double speed, and $\gamma _{1},\gamma _{2}$ with quadruple speed.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Thus, because of the differing speeds, the two paths are not identical.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] therefore crucially depends on the fact that paths are considered up to homotopy.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Indeed, both above composites are homotopic, for example, to the loop that traverses all three loops $\gamma _{0},\gamma _{1},\gamma _{2}$ with triple speed.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The set of based loops up to homotopy, equipped with the above operation therefore does turn $\pi _{1}(X,x_{0})$ into a group.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] This isomorphism is, in general, not unique: it depends on the choice of path up to homotopy.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] However changing the path results in changing the isomorphism between the two fundamental groups only by composition with an inner automorphism.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] It is therefore customary to write $\pi _{1}(X)$ instead of $\pi _{1}(X,x_{0})$ when the choice of basepoint does not matter.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] This section lists some basic examples of fundamental groups.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] To begin with, in Euclidean space ( $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ) or any convex subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{n},$ there is only one homotopy class of loops, and the fundamental group is therefore the trivial group with one element.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] More generally, any star domain – and yet more generally, any contractible space – has a trivial fundamental group.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Thus, the fundamental group does not distinguish between such spaces.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] A path-connected space whose fundamental group is trivial is called simply connected.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] For example, the 2-sphere $S^{2}=\left\{(x,y,z)\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}\mid x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}=1\right\}$ depicted on the right, and also all the higher-dimensional spheres, are simply-connected.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The figure illustrates a homotopy contracting one particular loop to the constant loop.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Instead, each homotopy class consists of all loops that wind around the circle a given number of times (which can be positive or negative, depending on the direction of winding).
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The product of a loop that winds around m times and another that winds around n times is a loop that winds around $m+n$ times.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Therefore, the fundamental group of the circle is isomorphic to $(\mathbb {Z} ,+),$ the additive group of integers.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] This fact can be used to give proofs of the Brouwer fixed point theorem and the Borsuk–Ulam theorem in dimension 2.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group of the figure eight is the free group on two letters.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] More generally, the fundamental group of a bouquet of r circles is the free group on r letters.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group of a wedge sum of two path connected spaces X and Y can be computed as the free product of the individual fundamental groups: $\pi _{1}(X\vee Y)\cong \pi _{1}(X)*\pi _{1}(Y)$ This generalizes the above observations since the figure eight is the wedge sum of two circles.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group of the plane punctured at n points is also the free group with n generators.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The i -th generator is the class of the loop that goes around the i -th puncture without going around any other punctures.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group can be defined for discrete structures too.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] In particular, consider a connected graph $G=(V,E)$ , with a designated vertex $v_{0}$ in V .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The loops in G are the cycles that start and end at $v_{0}$ .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Every simple loop in G contains exactly one edge in $E\setminus T$ ; every loop in G is a concatenation of such simple loops.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Therefore, the fundamental group of a graph is a free group, in which the number of generators is exactly the number of edges in $E\setminus T$ .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] For example, suppose G has 16 vertices arranged in 4 rows of 4 vertices each, with edges connecting vertices that are adjacent horizontally or vertically.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Then G has 24 edges overall, and the number of edges in each spanning tree is 16 − 1 = 15, so the fundamental group of G is the free group with 9 generators.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Note that G has 9 "holes", similarly to a bouquet of 9 circles, which has the same fundamental group.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group of a topological group X (with respect to the base point being the neutral element) is always commutative.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] In particular, the fundamental group of a Lie group is commutative.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] This binary operation $\star$ on the set of all loops is *a priori* independent from the one described above.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] However, the Eckmann–Hilton argument shows that it does in fact agree with the above concatenation of loops, and moreover that the resulting group structure is abelian.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] An inspection of the proof shows that, more generally, $\pi _{1}(X)$ is abelian for any H-space X , i.e., the multiplication need not have an inverse, nor does it have to be associative.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] For example, this shows that the fundamental group of a loop space of another topological space Y , $X=\Omega (Y),$ is abelian.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Related ideas lead to Heinz Hopf's computation of the cohomology of a Lie group.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] This mapping from continuous maps to group homomorphisms is compatible with composition of maps and identity morphisms.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] from the category of topological spaces together with a base point to the category of groups.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] It turns out that this functor does not distinguish maps that are homotopic relative to the base point: if $f,g:X\to Y$ are continuous maps with $f(x_{0})=g(x_{0})=y_{0}$ , and f and g are homotopic relative to $\{x_{0}\}$ , then $f_{*}=g_{*}$ .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] is a homotopy equivalence and therefore yields an isomorphism of their fundamental groups.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group functor takes products to products and coproducts to coproducts.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] (In the latter formula, $\vee$ denotes the wedge sum of pointed topological spaces, and * the free product of groups.) The latter formula is a special case of the Seifert–van Kampen theorem, which states that the fundamental group functor takes pushouts along inclusions to pushouts.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] As was mentioned above, computing the fundamental group of even relatively simple topological spaces tends to be not entirely trivial, but requires some methods of algebraic topology.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The abelianization of the fundamental group can be identified with the first homology group of the space.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] A special case of the Hurewicz theorem asserts that the first singular homology group $H_{1}(X)$ is, colloquially speaking, the closest approximation to the fundamental group by means of an abelian group.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] from the fundamental group of a topological space X to its first singular homology group $H_{1}(X).$ This homomorphism is not in general an isomorphism since the fundamental group may be non-abelian, but the homology group is, by definition, always abelian.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] This difference is, however, the only one: if X is path-connected, this homomorphism is surjective and its kernel is the commutator subgroup of the fundamental group, so that $H_{1}(X)$ is isomorphic to the abelianization of the fundamental group.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] For example, the 2-sphere $S^{2}$ can be obtained by gluing two copies of slightly overlapping half-spheres along a neighborhood of the equator.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] In this case the theorem yields $\pi _{1}(S^{2})$ is trivial, since the two half-spheres are contractible and therefore have trivial fundamental group.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental groups of surfaces, as mentioned above, can also be computed using this theorem.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] In the parlance of category theory, the theorem can be concisely stated by saying that the fundamental group functor takes pushouts (in the category of topological spaces) along inclusions to pushouts (in the category of groups).
[src:topology/fundamental-group] A covering is called a universal covering if E is, in addition to the preceding condition, simply connected.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] It is universal in the sense that all other coverings can be constructed by suitably identifying points in E .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] (or, equivalently, $\pi :\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} /\mathbb {Z} ,\ t\mapsto [t]$ ) is a universal covering.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Any path connected, locally path connected and locally simply connected topological space X admits a universal covering.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] An abstract construction proceeds analogously to the fundamental group by taking pairs $(x,\gamma )$ , where x is a point in X and $\gamma$ is a homotopy class of paths from $x_{0}$ to x .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The passage from a topological space to its universal covering can be used in understanding the geometry of X .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] For example, the uniformization theorem shows that any simply connected Riemann surface is (isomorphic to) either $S^{2},$ $\mathbb {C} ,$ or the upper half-plane.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] General Riemann surfaces then arise as quotients of group actions on these three surfaces.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Let G be a connected, simply connected compact Lie group, for example, the special unitary group ${\text{SU}}(n)$ , and let $\Gamma$ be a finite subgroup of G .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Then the homogeneous space $X=G/\Gamma$ has fundamental group $\Gamma$ , which acts by right multiplication on the universal covering space G .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] In this case the fundamental group is $\Gamma$ and the universal covering space $G/K$ is actually contractible (by the Cartan decomposition for Lie groups).
[src:topology/fundamental-group] As an example take $G={\text{SL}}(2,\mathbb {R} )$ , $K={\text{SO}}(2)$ and $\Gamma$ any torsion-free congruence subgroup of the modular group ${\text{SL}}(2,\mathbb {Z} )$ .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] From the explicit realization, it also follows that the universal covering space of a path connected topological group H is again a path connected topological group G .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Since G is a connected group with a continuous action by conjugation on a discrete group $\Gamma$ , it must act trivially, so that $\Gamma$ has to be a subgroup of the center of G .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] In particular $\pi _{1}(H)=\Gamma$ is an abelian group; this can also easily be seen directly without using covering spaces.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The group G is called the *universal covering group* of H .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] As the universal covering group suggests, there is an analogy between the fundamental group of a topological group and the center of a group; this is elaborated at Lattice of covering groups.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] which generalizes the above fact about the universal covering (which amounts to the case where the fiber F is also discrete).
[src:topology/fundamental-group] What is more, the sequence can be continued at the left with the higher homotopy groups $\pi _{n}$ of the three spaces, which gives some access to computing such groups in the same vein.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group of noncompact Lie groups can be reduced to the compact case, since such a group is homotopic to its maximal compact subgroup.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] A second method of computing fundamental groups applies to all connected compact Lie groups and uses the machinery of the maximal torus and the associated root system.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] can be shown to be surjective with kernel given by the set I of integer linear combination of coroots.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] This method shows, for example, that any connected compact Lie group for which the associated root system is of type $G_{2}$ is simply connected.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Thus, there is (up to isomorphism) only one connected compact Lie group having Lie algebra of type $G_{2}$ ; this group is simply connected and has trivial center.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] When the topological space is homeomorphic to a simplicial complex, its fundamental group can be described explicitly in terms of generators and relations.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] If X is a connected simplicial complex, an *edge-path* in X is defined to be a chain of vertices connected by edges in X .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Two edge-paths are said to be *edge-equivalent* if one can be obtained from the other by successively switching between an edge and the two opposite edges of a triangle in X .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] If v is a fixed vertex in X , an *edge-loop* at v is an edge-path starting and ending at v .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The **edge-path group** $E(X,v)$ is defined to be the set of edge-equivalence classes of edge-loops at v , with product and inverse defined by concatenation and reversal of edge-loops.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The edge-path group is naturally isomorphic to $\pi _{1}(|X|,v)$ , the fundamental group of the geometric realisation $|X|$ of X .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Since it depends only on the 2-skeleton $X^{2}$ of X (that is, the vertices, edges, and triangles of X ), the groups $\pi _{1}(|X|,v)$ and $\pi _{1}(|X^{2}|,v)$ are isomorphic.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The edge-path group can be described explicitly in terms of generators and relations.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] If T is a maximal spanning tree in the 1-skeleton of X , then $E(X,v)$ is canonically isomorphic to the group with generators (the oriented edge-paths of X not occurring in T ) and relations (the edge-equivalences corresponding to triangles in X ).
[src:topology/fundamental-group] A similar result holds if T is replaced by any simply connected—in particular contractible—subcomplex of X .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] This often gives a practical way of computing fundamental groups and can be used to show that every finitely presented group arises as the fundamental group of a finite simplicial complex.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] It is also one of the classical methods used for topological surfaces, which are classified by their fundamental groups.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The *universal covering space* of a finite connected simplicial complex X can also be described directly as a simplicial complex using edge-paths.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Its vertices are pairs $(w,\gamma )$ where w is a vertex of X and γ is an edge-equivalence class of paths from v to w .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The k -simplices containing $(w,\gamma )$ correspond naturally to the k -simplices containing w .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Each new vertex u of the k -simplex gives an edge $wu$ and hence, by concatenation, a new path $\gamma _{u}$ from v to u .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The points $(w,\gamma )$ and $(u,\gamma _{u})$ are the vertices of the "transported" simplex in the universal covering space.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The edge-path group acts naturally by concatenation, preserving the simplicial structure, and the quotient space is just X .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] It is well known that this method can also be used to compute the fundamental group of an arbitrary topological space.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] This was doubtless known to Eduard Čech and Jean Leray and explicitly appeared as a remark in a paper by André Weil; various other authors such as Lorenzo Calabi, Wu Wen-tsün, and Nodar Berikashvili have also published proofs.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] In the simplest case of a compact space X with a finite open covering in which all non-empty finite intersections of open sets in the covering are contractible, the fundamental group can be identified with the edge-path group of the simplicial complex corresponding to the nerve of the covering.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Roughly speaking, the fundamental group detects the 1-dimensional hole structure of a space, but not higher-dimensional holes such as for the 2-sphere.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Such "higher-dimensional holes" can be detected using the higher homotopy groups $\pi _{n}(X)$ , which are defined to consist of homotopy classes of (basepoint-preserving) maps from $S^{n}$ to X .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] As was mentioned in the above computation of $\pi _{1}$ of classical Lie groups, higher homotopy groups can be relevant even for computing fundamental groups.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The *fundamental groupoid* is a variant of the fundamental group that is useful in situations where the choice of a base point $x_{0}\in X$ is undesirable.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] where r is an arbitrary non-negative real number.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Since the length r is variable in this approach, such paths can be concatenated as is (i.e., not up to homotopy) and therefore yield a category.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The category of paths up to this equivalence relation is denoted $\Pi (X).$ Each morphism in $\Pi (X)$ is an isomorphism, with inverse given by the same path traversed in the opposite direction.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Generally speaking, representations may serve to exhibit features of a group by its actions on other mathematical objects, often vector spaces.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Conversely, any such representation on a path-connected space X arises in this manner.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] This equivalence of categories between representations of $\pi _{1}(X)$ and local systems is used, for example, in the study of differential equations, such as the Knizhnik–Zamolodchikov equations.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] In algebraic geometry, the so-called étale fundamental group is used as a replacement for the fundamental group.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Since the Zariski topology on an algebraic variety or scheme X is much coarser than, say, the topology of open subsets in $\mathbb {R} ^{n},$ it is no longer meaningful to consider continuous maps from an interval to X .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Instead, the approach developed by Grothendieck consists in constructing $\pi _{1}^{\text{et}}$ by considering all finite étale covers of X .
[src:topology/fundamental-group] These serve as an algebro-geometric analogue of coverings with finite fibers.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] This yields a theory applicable in situations where no great generality classical topological intuition whatsoever is available, for example for varieties defined over a finite field.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Also, the étale fundamental group of a field is its (absolute) Galois group.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] On the other hand, for smooth varieties X over the complex numbers, the étale fundamental group retains much of the information inherent in the classical fundamental group: the former is the profinite completion of the latter.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group of a root system is defined in analogy to the computation for Lie groups.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] This allows to define and use the fundamental group of a semisimple linear algebraic group G , which is a useful basic tool in the classification of linear algebraic groups.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The homotopy relation between 1-simplices of a simplicial set X is an equivalence relation if X is a Kan complex but not necessarily so in general.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] Thus, $\pi _{1}$ of a Kan complex can be defined as the set of homotopy classes of 1-simplices.
[src:topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group of an arbitrary simplicial set X are defined to be the homotopy group of its topological realization, $|X|,$ i.e., the topological space obtained by gluing topological simplices as prescribed by the simplicial set structure of X .
[src:topology/homeomorphism] Homeomorphisms are the isomorphisms in the category of topological spaces—that is, they are the mappings that preserve all the topological properties of a given space.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] Two spaces with a homeomorphism between them are called **homeomorphic**, and from a topological viewpoint they are the same.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] Very roughly speaking, a topological space is a geometric object, and a homeomorphism results from a continuous deformation of the object into a new shape.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] Thus, a square and a circle are homeomorphic to each other, but a sphere and a torus are not.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] However, this description can be misleading.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] Some continuous deformations do not produce homeomorphisms, such as the deformation of a line into a point.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] Some homeomorphisms do not result from continuous deformations, such as the homeomorphism between a trefoil knot and a circle.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] Homotopy and isotopy are precise definitions for the informal concept of *continuous deformation*.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] A homeomorphism is sometimes called a *bicontinuous* function.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] If such a function exists, X and Y are **homeomorphic**.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] A **self-homeomorphism** is a homeomorphism from a topological space onto itself.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] Being "homeomorphic" is an equivalence relation on topological spaces.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] Its equivalence classes are called **homeomorphism classes**.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] The third requirement, that ${\textstyle f^{-1}}$ be continuous, is essential.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] Homeomorphisms are the isomorphisms in the category of topological spaces.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] In some contexts, there are homeomorphic objects that cannot be continuously deformed from one to the other.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] Homotopy and isotopy are equivalence relations that have been introduced for dealing with such situations.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] The intuitive criterion of stretching, bending, cutting and gluing back together takes a certain amount of practice to apply correctly—it may not be obvious from the description above that deforming a line segment to a point is impermissible, for instance.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] It is thus important to realize that it is the formal definition given above that counts.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] In this case, for example, the line segment possesses infinitely many points, and therefore cannot be put into a bijection with a set containing only a finite number of points, including a single point.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] This characterization of a homeomorphism often leads to a confusion with the concept of homotopy, which is actually *defined* as a continuous deformation, but from one *function* to another, rather than one space to another.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] In the case of a homeomorphism, envisioning a continuous deformation is a mental tool for keeping track of which points on space *X* correspond to which points on *Y*—one just follows them as *X* deforms.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] In the case of homotopy, the continuous deformation from one map to the other is of the essence, and it is also less restrictive, since none of the maps involved need to be one-to-one or onto.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] Homotopy does lead to a relation on spaces: homotopy equivalence.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] There is a name for the kind of deformation involved in visualizing a homeomorphism.
[src:topology/homeomorphism] It is (except when cutting and regluing are required) an isotopy between the identity map on *X* and the homeomorphism from *X* to *Y*.
[src:topology/homotopy] A notable use of homotopy is the definition of homotopy groups and cohomotopy groups, important invariants in algebraic topology.
[src:topology/homotopy] In practice, there are technical difficulties in using homotopies with certain spaces.
[src:topology/homotopy] Algebraic topologists work with compactly generated spaces, CW complexes, or spectra.
[src:topology/homotopy] If we think of the second parameter of *H* as time, then *H* describes a *continuous deformation* of *f* into *g*: at time 0, we have the function *f*, and at time 1, we have the function *g*.
[src:topology/homotopy] We can also think of the second parameter as a "slider control" that allows us to smoothly transition from *f* to *g* as the slider moves from 0 to 1, and vice versa.
[src:topology/homotopy] An alternative notation is to say that a homotopy between two continuous functions $f,g:X\to Y$ is a family of continuous functions $h_{t}:X\to Y$ for $t\in [0,1]$ such that $h_{0}=f$ and $h_{1}=g$ , and the map $(x,t)\mapsto h_{t}(x)$ is continuous from $X\times [0,1]$ to Y .
[src:topology/homotopy] The two versions coincide by setting $h_{t}(x)=H(x,t)$ .
[src:topology/homotopy] It is not sufficient to require each map $h_{t}(x)$ to be continuous.
[src:topology/homotopy] The animation that is looped above right provides an example of a homotopy between two embeddings, *f* and *g*, of the torus into *R*3.
[src:topology/homotopy] *X* is the torus, *Y* is *R*3, *f* is some continuous function from the torus to *R*3 that takes the torus to the embedded surface-of-a-doughnut shape with which the animation starts; *g* is some continuous function that takes the torus to the embedded surface-of-a-coffee-mug shape.
[src:topology/homotopy] The animation shows the image of *h**t*(X) as a function of the parameter *t*, where *t* varies with time from 0 to 1 over each cycle of the animation loop.
[src:topology/homotopy] It pauses, then shows the image as *t* varies back from 1 to 0, pauses, and repeats this cycle.
[src:topology/homotopy] Continuous functions *f* and *g* are said to be homotopic if and only if there is a homotopy *H* taking *f* to *g* as described above.
[src:topology/homotopy] Being homotopic is an equivalence relation on the set of all continuous functions from *X* to *Y*.
[src:topology/homotopy] This homotopy relation is compatible with function composition in the following sense: if *f*1, *g*1 : *X* → *Y* are homotopic, and *f*2, *g*2 : *Y* → *Z* are homotopic, then their compositions *f*2 ∘ *f*1 and *g*2 ∘ *g*1 : *X* → *Z* are also homotopic.
[src:topology/homotopy] Given two topological spaces *X* and *Y*, a **homotopy equivalence** between *X* and *Y* is a pair of continuous maps *f* : *X* → *Y* and *g* : *Y* → *X*, such that *g* ∘ *f* is homotopic to the identity map id*X* and *f* ∘ *g* is homotopic to id*Y*.
[src:topology/homotopy] If such a pair exists, then *X* and *Y* are said to be **homotopy equivalent**, or of the same **homotopy type**.
[src:topology/homotopy] This relation of homotopy equivalence is often denoted $\simeq$ .
[src:topology/homotopy] Intuitively, two spaces *X* and *Y* are homotopy equivalent if they can be transformed into one another by bending, shrinking and expanding operations.
[src:topology/homotopy] Spaces that are homotopy equivalent to a point are called contractible.
[src:topology/homotopy] A homeomorphism is a special case of a homotopy equivalence, in which *g* ∘ *f* is equal to the identity map id*X* (not only homotopic to it), and *f* ∘ *g* is equal to id*Y*.
[src:topology/homotopy] Therefore, if X and Y are homeomorphic, then they are homotopy equivalent, but the opposite is not true.
[src:topology/homotopy] A function f is said to be **null-homotopic** if it is homotopic to a constant function.
[src:topology/homotopy] (The homotopy from f to a constant function is then sometimes called a **null-homotopy**.) For example, a map f from the unit circle $S^{1}$ to any space X is null-homotopic precisely when it can be continuously extended to a map from the unit disk $D^{2}$ to X that agrees with f on the boundary.
[src:topology/homotopy] It follows from these definitions that a space X is contractible if and only if the identity map from X to itself—which is always a homotopy equivalence—is null-homotopic.
[src:topology/homotopy] Homotopy equivalence is important because in algebraic topology many concepts are **homotopy invariant**, that is, they respect the relation of homotopy equivalence.
[src:topology/homotopy] An example of an algebraic invariant of topological spaces which is not homotopy invariant is compactly supported homology (which is, roughly speaking, the homology of the compactification, and compactification is not homotopy invariant).
[src:topology/homotopy] In order to define the fundamental group, one needs the notion of **homotopy relative to a subspace**.
[src:topology/homotopy] These are homotopies which keep the elements of the subspace fixed.
[src:topology/homotopy] Also, if *g* is a retraction from *X* to *K* and *f* is the identity map, this is known as a strong deformation retract of *X* to *K*.
[src:topology/homotopy] When *K* is a point, the term **pointed homotopy** is used.
[src:topology/homotopy] since one cannot be deformed into the other through a continuous path of homeomorphisms of the ambient space.
[src:topology/homotopy] When two given continuous functions *f* and *g* from the topological space *X* to the topological space *Y* are embeddings, one can ask whether they can be connected 'through embeddings'.
[src:topology/homotopy] This gives rise to the concept of **isotopy**, which is a homotopy, *H*, in the notation used before, such that for each fixed *t*, *H*(*x*, *t*) gives an embedding.
[src:topology/homotopy] A related, but separate, concept is that of ambient isotopy.
[src:topology/homotopy] Requiring that two embeddings be isotopic is a stronger requirement than that they be homotopic.
[src:topology/homotopy] For example, the map from the interval [−1, 1] into the real numbers defined by *f*(*x*) = −*x* is *not* isotopic to the identity *g*(*x*) = *x*.
[src:topology/homotopy] Any homotopy from *f* to the identity would have to exchange the endpoints, which would mean that they would have to 'pass through' each other.
[src:topology/homotopy] Moreover, *f* has changed the orientation of the interval and *g* has not, which is impossible under an isotopy.
[src:topology/homotopy] Two homeomorphisms (which are special cases of embeddings) of the unit ball which agree on the boundary can be shown to be isotopic using Alexander's trick.
[src:topology/homotopy] For this reason, the map of the unit disc in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ defined by *f*(*x*, *y*) = (−*x*, −*y*) is isotopic to a 180-degree rotation around the origin, and so the identity map and *f* are isotopic because they can be connected by rotations.
[src:topology/homotopy] In geometric topology—for example, in knot theory—the idea of isotopy is used to construct equivalence relations.
[src:topology/homotopy] For example, when should two knots be considered the same?
[src:topology/homotopy] We take two knots, *K*1 and *K*2, in three-dimensional space.
[src:topology/homotopy] A knot is an embedding of a one-dimensional space, the "loop of string" (or the circle), into this space, and this embedding gives a homeomorphism between the circle and its image in the embedding space.
[src:topology/homotopy] One may try to define knot equivalence based on isotopy instead of the more restricted property of ambient isotopy.
[src:topology/homotopy] That is, two knots are isotopic when there exists a continuous function starting at *t* = 0 giving the *K*1 embedding, ending at *t* = 1 giving the *K*2 embedding, with all intermediate values corresponding to embeddings.
[src:topology/homotopy] However, this definition would make every knot equivalent to the unknot, as the knotted portions can be "contracted" down to a straight line.
[src:topology/homotopy] The problem is that, while continuous, this is not an injective function of the Euclidean space that the knot is embedded in.
[src:topology/homotopy] An ambient isotopy, studied in this context, is an isotopy of the larger space, considered in light of its action on the embedded submanifold.
[src:topology/homotopy] Knots *K*1 and *K*2 are considered equivalent when there is a continuous [0, 1]-indexed family of maps which moves *K*1 to *K*2 via homeomorphisms of the Euclidean space.
[src:topology/homotopy] Similar language is used for the equivalent concept in contexts where one has a stronger notion of equivalence.
[src:topology/homotopy] For example, a path between two smooth embeddings is a **smooth isotopy**.
[src:topology/homotopy] On a Lorentzian manifold, certain curves are distinguished as timelike (representing something that only goes forwards, not backwards, in time, in every local frame).
[src:topology/homotopy] A timelike homotopy between two timelike curves is a homotopy such that the curve remains timelike during the continuous transformation from one curve to another.
[src:topology/homotopy] No closed timelike curve (CTC) on a Lorentzian manifold is timelike homotopic to a point (that is, null timelike homotopic); such a manifold is therefore said to be multiply connected by timelike curves.
[src:topology/homotopy] A manifold such as the 3-sphere can be simply connected (by any type of curve), and yet be timelike multiply connected.
[src:topology/homotopy] The homotopy lifting property is used to characterize fibrations.
[src:topology/homotopy] Another useful property involving homotopy is the homotopy extension property, which characterizes the extension of a homotopy between two functions from a subset of some set to the set itself.
[src:topology/homotopy] It is useful when dealing with cofibrations.
[src:topology/homotopy] Since the relation of two functions $f,g\colon X\to Y$ being homotopic relative to a subspace is an equivalence relation, we can look at the equivalence classes of maps between a fixed *X* and *Y*.
[src:topology/homotopy] If we fix $X=[0,1]^{n}$ , the unit interval [0, 1] crossed with itself *n* times, and we take its boundary $\partial ([0,1]^{n})$ as a subspace, then the equivalence classes form a group, denoted $\pi _{n}(Y,y_{0})$ , where $y_{0}$ is in the image of the subspace $\partial ([0,1]^{n})$ .
[src:topology/homotopy] We can define the action of one equivalence class on another, and so we get a group.
[src:topology/homotopy] These groups are called the homotopy groups.
[src:topology/homotopy] In the case $n=1$ , it is also called the fundamental group.
[src:topology/homotopy] The idea of homotopy can be turned into a formal category of category theory.
[src:topology/homotopy] The **homotopy category** is the category whose objects are topological spaces, and whose morphisms are homotopy equivalence classes of continuous maps.
[src:topology/homotopy] Two topological spaces *X* and *Y* are isomorphic in this category if and only if they are homotopy equivalent.
[src:topology/homotopy] Then a functor on the category of topological spaces is homotopy invariant if it can be expressed as a functor on the homotopy category.
[src:topology/homotopy] For example, homology groups are a *functorial* homotopy invariant: this means that if *f* and *g* from *X* to *Y* are homotopic, then the group homomorphisms induced by *f* and *g* on the level of homology groups are the same: H*n*(*f*) = H*n*(*g*) : H*n*(*X*) → H*n*(*Y*) for all *n*.
[src:topology/homotopy] Likewise, if *X* and *Y* are in addition path-connected, and the homotopy between *f* and *g* is pointed, then the group homomorphisms induced by *f* and *g* on the level of homotopy groups are also the same: π*n*(*f*) = π*n*(*g*) : π*n*(*X*) → π*n*(*Y*).
[src:topology/homotopy] Based on the concept of the homotopy, computation methods for algebraic and differential equations have been developed.
[src:topology/homotopy] The methods for algebraic equations include the homotopy continuation method and the continuation method (see numerical continuation).
[src:topology/homotopy] The methods for differential equations include the homotopy analysis method.
[src:topology/homotopy] Homotopy theory can be used as a foundation for homology theory: one can represent a cohomology functor on a space *X* by mappings of *X* into an appropriate fixed space, up to homotopy equivalence.
[src:topology/homotopy] For example, for any abelian group *G*, and any based CW-complex *X*, the set $[X,K(G,n)]$ of based homotopy classes of based maps from *X* to the Eilenberg–MacLane space $K(G,n)$ is in natural bijection with the *n*-th singular cohomology group $H^{n}(X,G)$ of the space *X*.
[src:topology/homotopy] One says that the omega-spectrum of Eilenberg-MacLane spaces are representing spaces for singular cohomology with coefficients in *G*.
[src:topology/homotopy] Using this fact, homotopy classes between a CW complex and a multiply connected space can be calculated using cohomology as described by the Hopf–Whitney theorem.
[src:topology/homotopy] Recently, homotopy theory is used to develop deep learning-based generative models like diffusion models and flow-based generative models.
[src:topology/homotopy] Perturbing the complex non-Gaussian states is a tough task.
[src:topology/homotopy] Using deep learning and homotopy, such complex states can be transformed to Gaussian state and mildly perturbed to get transformed back to perturbed complex states.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In mathematics, a **manifold** is a topological space that locally resembles Euclidean space near each point.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] More precisely, an n -dimensional manifold, or *n -manifold* for short, is a topological space with the property that each point has a neighborhood that is homeomorphic to an open subset of n -dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] One-dimensional manifolds include lines and circles, but not self-crossing curves such as a figure-eight.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Two-dimensional manifolds are also called surfaces.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Examples include the plane, the sphere, and the torus, and also the Klein bottle and real projective plane.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The concept of a manifold is central to many parts of geometry and modern mathematical physics because it allows complicated structures to be described in terms of well-understood topological properties of simpler spaces.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Manifolds naturally arise as solution sets of systems of equations and as graphs of functions.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The concept has applications in computer-graphics given the need to associate pictures with coordinates (e.g.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Manifolds can be equipped with additional structure.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] One important class of manifolds are differentiable manifolds; their differentiable structure allows calculus to be done.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A Riemannian metric on a manifold allows distances and angles to be measured.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Symplectic manifolds serve as the phase spaces in the Hamiltonian formalism of classical mechanics, while four-dimensional Lorentzian manifolds model spacetime in general relativity.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The study of manifolds requires working knowledge of calculus and topology.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] After a line, a circle is the simplest example of a topological manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Topology ignores bending, so a small piece of a circle is treated the same as a small piece of a line.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Considering, for instance, the top part of the unit circle, *x*2 + *y*2 = 1, where the *y*-coordinate is positive (indicated by the yellow arc in *Figure 1*).
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Any point of this arc can be uniquely described by its *x*-coordinate.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Such functions along with the open regions they map are called *charts*.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Together, these parts cover the whole circle, and the four charts form an atlas for the circle.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The top and right charts, $\chi _{\mathrm {top} }$ and $\chi _{\mathrm {right} }$ respectively, overlap in their domain: their intersection lies in the quarter of the circle where both x and y -coordinates are positive.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Both map this part into the interval $(0,1)$ , though differently.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Thus a function $T:(0,1)\rightarrow (0,1)=\chi _{\mathrm {right} }\circ \chi _{\mathrm {top} }^{-1}$ can be constructed, which takes values from the co-domain of $\chi _{\mathrm {top} }$ back to the circle using the inverse, followed by $\chi _{\mathrm {right} }$ back to the interval.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Such a function is called a *transition map*.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The top, bottom, left, and right charts do not form the only possible atlas.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Charts need not be geometric projections, and the number of charts is a matter of choice.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Here *s* is the slope of the line through the point at coordinates (*x*, *y*) and the fixed pivot point (−1, 0); similarly, *t* is the opposite of the slope of the line through the points at coordinates (*x*, *y*) and (+1, 0).
[src:topology/manifold-p01] It can be confirmed that *x*2 + *y*2 = 1 for all values of *s* and *t*.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] These two charts provide a second atlas for the circle, with the transition map $t={\frac {1}{s}}$ (that is, one has this relation between *s* and *t* for every point where *s* and *t* are both nonzero).
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Each chart omits a single point, either (−1, 0) for *s* or (+1, 0) for *t*, so neither chart alone is sufficient to cover the whole circle.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] It can be proved that it is not possible to cover the full circle with a single chart.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] For example, although it is possible to construct a circle from a single line interval by overlapping and "gluing" the ends, this does not produce a chart; a portion of the circle will be mapped to both ends at once, losing invertibility.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] may be covered by an atlas of six charts: the plane *z* = 0 divides the sphere into two half spheres (*z* > 0 and *z* < 0), which may both be mapped on the disc *x*2 + *y*2 < 1 by the projection on the *xy* plane of coordinates.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This provides two charts; the four other charts are provided by a similar construction with the two other coordinate planes.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] As with the circle, one may define one chart that covers the whole sphere excluding one point.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Thus two charts are sufficient, but the sphere cannot be covered by a single chart.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Manifolds do not need to be connected (all in "one piece"); an example is a pair of separate circles.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Manifolds need not be closed; thus a line segment without its end points is a manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] They are never countable, unless the dimension of the manifold is 0.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Putting these freedoms together, other examples of manifolds are a parabola, a hyperbola, and the locus of points on a cubic curve *y*2 = *x*3 − *x* (a closed loop piece and an open, infinite piece).
[src:topology/manifold-p01] However, excluded are examples like two touching circles that share a point to form a figure-8; at the shared point, a satisfactory chart cannot be created.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Even with the bending allowed by topology, the vicinity of the shared point looks like a "+", not a line.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A "+" is not homeomorphic to a line segment, since deleting the center point from the "+" gives a space with four components (i.e. pieces), whereas deleting a point from a line segment gives a space with at most two pieces; topological operations always preserve the number of pieces.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Informally, a manifold is a space that is "modeled on" Euclidean space.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A manifold can be given additional structure if the patching functions satisfy axioms beyond continuity.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] For instance, differentiable manifolds have homeomorphisms on overlapping neighborhoods diffeomorphic with each other, so that the manifold has a well-defined set of functions which are differentiable in each neighborhood, thus differentiable on the manifold as a whole.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Formally, a (topological) manifold is a second countable Hausdorff space that is locally homeomorphic to a Euclidean space.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The n that appears in the preceding definition is called the *local dimension* of the manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Generally manifolds are taken to have a constant local dimension, and the local dimension is then called the *dimension* of the manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This is, in particular, the case when manifolds are connected.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] However, some authors admit manifolds that are not connected, and where different points can have different dimensions.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] If a manifold has a fixed dimension, this can be emphasized by calling it a **pure manifold**.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] For example, the (surface of a) sphere has a constant dimension of 2 and is therefore a pure manifold whereas the disjoint union of a sphere and a line in three-dimensional space is *not* a pure manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Since dimension is a local invariant (i.e. the map sending each point to the dimension of its neighbourhood over which a chart is defined, is locally constant), each connected component has a fixed dimension.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Sheaf-theoretically, a manifold is a locally ringed space, whose structure sheaf is locally isomorphic to the sheaf of continuous (or differentiable, or complex-analytic, etc.) functions on Euclidean space.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This definition is mostly used when discussing analytic manifolds in algebraic geometry.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The spherical Earth is navigated using flat maps or charts, collected in an atlas.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Similarly, a manifold can be described using mathematical maps, called *coordinate charts*, collected in a mathematical *atlas*.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] It is not generally possible to describe a manifold with just one chart, because the global structure of the manifold is different from the simple structure of the charts.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] For example, no single flat map can represent the entire Earth without separation of adjacent features across the map's boundaries or duplication of coverage.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] When a manifold is constructed from multiple overlapping charts, the regions where they overlap carry information essential to understanding the global structure.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A *coordinate map*, a *coordinate chart*, or simply a *chart*, of a manifold is an invertible map between a subset of the manifold and a simple space such that both the map and its inverse preserve the desired structure.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] For a topological manifold, the simple space is a subset of some Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ and interest focuses on the topological structure.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This structure is preserved by homeomorphisms, invertible maps that are continuous in both directions.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In the case of a differentiable manifold, a set of *charts* called an *atlas*, whose *transition functions* (see below) are all differentiable, allows us to do calculus on it.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Polar coordinates, for example, form a chart for the plane $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ minus the positive *x*-axis and the origin.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Another example of a chart is the map χtop mentioned above, a chart for the circle.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The description of most manifolds requires more than one chart.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A specific collection of charts which covers a manifold is called an *atlas*.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] An atlas is not unique as all manifolds can be covered in multiple ways using different combinations of charts.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Two atlases are said to be equivalent if their union is also an atlas.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The atlas containing all possible charts consistent with a given atlas is called the *maximal atlas* (i.e. an equivalence class containing that given atlas).
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Unlike an ordinary atlas, the maximal atlas of a given manifold is unique.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Though useful for definitions, it is an abstract object and not used directly (e.g. in calculations).
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A manifold can be defined as a topological space equipped with an atlas (and in some definitions, a maximal atlas).
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Charts in an atlas may overlap and a single point of a manifold may be represented in several charts.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] If two charts overlap, parts of them represent the same region of the manifold, just as a map of Europe and a map of Russia may both contain Moscow.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Given two overlapping charts, a *transition function* can be defined which goes from an open ball in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ to the manifold and then back to another (or perhaps the same) open ball in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The resultant map, like the map *T* in the circle example above, is called a *change of coordinates*, a *coordinate transformation*, a *transition function*, or a *transition map*.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] An atlas can also be used to define additional structure on the manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The structure is first defined on each chart separately.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] If all transition maps are compatible with this structure, the structure transfers to the manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This is the standard way differentiable manifolds are defined.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] If the transition functions of an atlas for a topological manifold preserve the natural differential structure of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ (that is, if they are diffeomorphisms), the differential structure transfers to the manifold and turns it into a differentiable manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Complex manifolds are introduced in an analogous way by requiring that the transition functions of an atlas are holomorphic functions.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] For symplectic manifolds, the transition functions must be symplectomorphisms.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The structure on the manifold depends on the atlas, but sometimes different atlases can be said to give rise to the same structure.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] These notions are made precise in general through the use of pseudogroups.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A **manifold with boundary** is a manifold with an edge.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] For example, a disk (circle plus interior) is a 2-manifold with boundary the circle, a 1-manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The boundary of an n -manifold with boundary is an $(n-1)$ -manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In three dimensions, a ball (sphere plus interior) is a 3-manifold with boundary.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In technical language, a manifold with boundary is a space containing both interior points and boundary points.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Every interior point has a neighborhood homeomorphic to the open n -ball $\textstyle \{(x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n})\mid \sum x_{i}^{2}<1\}$ .
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Any homeomorphism between half-balls must send points with $x_{1}=0$ to points with $x_{1}=0$ .
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This invariance allows us to define boundary points on the manifold with boundary (see next paragraph).
[src:topology/manifold-p01] If in addition we are considering differentiable manifolds, then a square with interior is not a manifold with boundary.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The four vertices are neither locally diffeomorphic to Euclidean space nor to Euclidean half-space.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This is an example of a differentiable manifold with corners.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Similarly, products of differentiable manifolds with boundaries are not generally differentiable manifolds with boundaries, but instead are differentiable manifolds with corners.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The **interior** of M , denoted $\operatorname {Int} M$ , is the set of points in M which have neighborhoods homeomorphic to an open subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The **boundary** of M , denoted $\partial M$ , is the complement of $\operatorname {Int} M$ in M .
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The boundary points can be characterized as those points which land on the boundary hyperplane $(x_{n}=0)$ of $\mathbb {R} _{+}^{n}$ under some coordinate chart.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] If M is a manifold with boundary of dimension n , then $\operatorname {Int} M$ is a manifold (without boundary) of dimension n and $\partial M$ is a manifold (without boundary) of dimension $n-1$ .
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A single manifold can be constructed in different ways, each stressing a different aspect of the manifold, thereby leading to a slightly different viewpoint.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Perhaps the simplest way to construct a manifold is the one used in the example above of the circle.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] First, a subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ is identified, and then an atlas covering this subset is constructed.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The concept of *manifold* grew historically from constructions like this.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A sphere can be treated in almost the same way as the circle.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The sphere is two-dimensional, so each chart will map part of the sphere to an open subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Consider the northern hemisphere, which is the part with positive *z* coordinate (coloured red in the picture on the right).
[src:topology/manifold-p01] maps the northern hemisphere to the open unit disc by projecting it on the (*x*, *y*) plane.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A similar chart exists for the southern hemisphere.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Together with two charts projecting on the (*x*, *z*) plane and two charts projecting on the (*y*, *z*) plane, an atlas of six charts is obtained which covers the entire sphere.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This can be easily generalized to higher-dimensional spheres.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A manifold can be constructed by gluing together pieces in a consistent manner, making them into overlapping charts.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This construction is possible for any manifold and hence it is often used as a characterisation, especially for differentiable and Riemannian manifolds.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] It focuses on an atlas, as the patches naturally provide charts, and since there is no exterior space involved it leads to an intrinsic view of the manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The manifold is constructed by specifying an atlas, which is itself defined by transition maps.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A point of the manifold is therefore an equivalence class of points which are mapped to each other by transition maps.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Charts map equivalence classes to points of a single patch.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] There are usually strong demands on the consistency of the transition maps.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] For topological manifolds they are required to be homeomorphisms; if they are also diffeomorphisms, the resulting manifold is a differentiable manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This can be illustrated with the transition map *t* = 1⁄*s* from the second half of the circle example.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Use the coordinate *s* for the first copy, and *t* for the second copy.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Now, glue both copies together by identifying the point *t* on the second copy with the point *s* = 1⁄*t* on the first copy (the points *t* = 0 and *s* = 0 are not identified with any point on the first and second copy, respectively).
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The first construction and this construction are very similar, but represent rather different points of view.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In the first construction, the manifold is seen as embedded in some Euclidean space.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] When a manifold is viewed in this way, it is easy to use intuition from Euclidean spaces to define additional structure.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] For example, in a Euclidean space, it is always clear whether a vector at some point is tangential or normal to some surface through that point.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The patchwork construction does not use any embedding, but simply views the manifold as a topological space by itself.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This abstract point of view is called the *intrinsic view*.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] It can make it harder to imagine what a tangent vector might be, and there is no intrinsic notion of a normal bundle, but instead there is an intrinsic stable normal bundle.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The *n*-sphere **S***n* is a generalisation of the idea of a circle (1-sphere) and sphere (2-sphere) to higher dimensions.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] An *n*-sphere **S***n* can be constructed by gluing together two copies of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This function is its own inverse and thus can be used in both directions.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] As the transition map is a smooth function, this atlas defines a smooth manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In the case *n* = 1, the example simplifies to the circle example given earlier.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] It is possible to define different points of a manifold to be the same point.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This can be visualized as gluing these points together in a single point, forming a quotient space.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] There is, however, no reason to expect such quotient spaces to be manifolds.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Among the possible quotient spaces that are not necessarily manifolds, orbifolds and CW complexes are considered to be relatively well-behaved.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] An example of a quotient space of a manifold that is also a manifold is the real projective space, identified as a quotient space of the corresponding sphere.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] One method of identifying points (gluing them together) is through a right (or left) action of a group, which acts on the manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Two points are identified if one is moved onto the other by some group element.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] If *M* is the manifold and *G* is the group, the resulting quotient space is denoted by *M* / *G* (or *G* \ *M*).
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Manifolds which can be constructed by identifying points include tori and real projective spaces (starting with a plane and a sphere, respectively).
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Two manifolds with boundaries can be glued together along a boundary.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] If this is done the right way, the result is also a manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Similarly, two boundaries of a single manifold can be glued together.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Formally, the gluing is defined by a bijection between the two boundaries.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Two points are identified when they are mapped onto each other.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] For a topological manifold, this bijection should be a homeomorphism, otherwise the result will not be a topological manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Similarly, for a differentiable manifold, it has to be a diffeomorphism.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] For other manifolds, other structures should be preserved.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A finite cylinder may be constructed as a manifold by starting with a strip [0,1] × [0,1] and gluing a pair of opposite edges on the boundary by a suitable diffeomorphism.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A projective plane may be obtained by gluing a sphere with a hole in it to a Möbius strip along their respective circular boundaries.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The Cartesian product of manifolds is also a manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The dimension of the product manifold is the sum of the dimensions of its factors.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Its topology is the product topology, and a Cartesian product of charts is a chart for the product manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Thus, an atlas for the product manifold can be constructed using atlases for its factors.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] If these atlases define a differential structure on the factors, the corresponding atlas defines a differential structure on the product manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The same is true for any other structure defined on the factors.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] If one of the factors has a boundary, the product manifold also has a boundary.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Cartesian products may be used to construct tori and finite cylinders, for example, as **S**1 × **S**1 and **S**1 × [0,1], respectively.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The study of manifolds combines many important areas of mathematics: it generalizes concepts such as curves and surfaces as well as ideas from linear algebra and topology.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Before the modern concept of a manifold there were several important results.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Non-Euclidean geometry considers spaces where Euclid's parallel postulate fails.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Saccheri first studied such geometries in 1733, but sought only to disprove them.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Gauss, Bolyai and Lobachevsky independently discovered them 100 years later.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Their research uncovered two types of spaces whose geometric structures differ from that of classical Euclidean space; these gave rise to hyperbolic geometry and elliptic geometry.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In the modern theory of manifolds, these notions correspond to Riemannian manifolds with constant negative and positive curvature, respectively.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Carl Friedrich Gauss may have been the first to consider abstract spaces as mathematical objects in their own right.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] His theorema egregium gives a method for computing the curvature of a surface without considering the ambient space in which the surface lies.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Such a surface would, in modern terminology, be called a manifold; and in modern terms, the theorem proved that the curvature of the surface is an intrinsic property.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Manifold theory has come to focus exclusively on these intrinsic properties (or invariants), while largely ignoring the extrinsic properties of the ambient space.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Another, more topological example of an intrinsic property of a manifold is its Euler characteristic.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Thus 2 is a topological invariant of the sphere, called its **Euler characteristic**.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] On the other hand, a torus can be sliced open by its 'parallel' and 'meridian' circles, creating a map with *V* = 1 vertex, *E* = 2 edges, and *F* = 1 face.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Thus the Euler characteristic of the torus is 1 − 2 + 1 = 0.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The Euler characteristic of other surfaces is a useful topological invariant, which can be extended to higher dimensions using Betti numbers.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In the mid nineteenth century, the Gauss–Bonnet theorem linked the Euler characteristic to the Gaussian curvature.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Investigations of Niels Henrik Abel and Carl Gustav Jacobi on inversion of elliptic integrals in the first half of 19th century led them to consider special types of complex manifolds, now known as Jacobians.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Bernhard Riemann further contributed to their theory, clarifying the geometric meaning of the process of analytic continuation of functions of complex variables.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Another important source of manifolds in 19th century mathematics was analytical mechanics, as developed by Siméon Poisson, Jacobi, and William Rowan Hamilton.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The possible states of a mechanical system are thought to be points of an abstract space, phase space in Lagrangian and Hamiltonian formalisms of classical mechanics.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This space is, in fact, a high-dimensional manifold, whose dimension corresponds to the degrees of freedom of the system and where the points are specified by their generalized coordinates.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] For an unconstrained movement of free particles the manifold is equivalent to the Euclidean space, but various conservation laws constrain it to more complicated formations, e.g.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The theory of a rotating solid body, developed in the 18th century by Leonhard Euler and Joseph-Louis Lagrange, gives another example where the manifold is nontrivial.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Geometrical and topological aspects of classical mechanics were emphasized by Henri Poincaré, one of the founders of topology.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Riemann was the first one to do extensive work generalizing the idea of a surface to higher dimensions.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The name *manifold* comes from Riemann's original German term, *Mannigfaltigkeit*, which William Kingdon Clifford translated as "manifoldness".
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In his Göttingen inaugural lecture, Riemann described the set of all possible values of a variable with certain constraints as a *Mannigfaltigkeit*, because the variable can have *many* values.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] He distinguishes between *stetige Mannigfaltigkeit* and *diskrete* *Mannigfaltigkeit* (*continuous manifoldness* and *discontinuous manifoldness*), depending on whether the value changes continuously or not.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] As continuous examples, Riemann refers to not only colors and the locations of objects in space, but also the possible shapes of a spatial figure.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Using induction, Riemann constructs an *n-fach ausgedehnte Mannigfaltigkeit* (*n times extended manifoldness* or *n-dimensional manifoldness*) as a continuous stack of (n−1) dimensional manifoldnesses.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Riemann's intuitive notion of a *Mannigfaltigkeit* evolved into what is today formalized as a manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Riemannian manifolds and Riemann surfaces are named after Riemann.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In his very influential paper, Analysis Situs, Henri Poincaré gave a definition of a differentiable manifold (*variété*) which served as a precursor to the modern concept of a manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In the first section of Analysis Situs, Poincaré defines a manifold as the level set of a continuously differentiable function between Euclidean spaces that satisfies the nondegeneracy hypothesis of the implicit function theorem.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In the third section, he begins by remarking that the graph of a continuously differentiable function is a manifold in the latter sense.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] He then proposes a new, more general, definition of manifold based on a 'chain of manifolds' (*une chaîne des variétés*).
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Poincaré's notion of a *chain of manifolds* is a precursor to the modern notion of atlas.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In particular, he considers two manifolds defined respectively as graphs of functions $\theta (y)$ and $\theta '\left(y'\right)$ .
[src:topology/manifold-p01] If these manifolds overlap (*a une partie commune*), then he requires that the coordinates y depend continuously differentiably on the coordinates $y'$ and vice versa ('*...les y sont fonctions analytiques des $y'$ et inversement*').
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In this way he introduces a precursor to the notion of a chart and of a transition map.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The circle can be represented by a graph in the neighborhood of every point because the left hand side of its defining equation $x^{2}+y^{2}-1=0$ has nonzero gradient at every point of the circle.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] By the implicit function theorem, every submanifold of Euclidean space is locally the graph of a function.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Hermann Weyl gave an intrinsic definition for differentiable manifolds in his lecture course on Riemann surfaces in 1911–1912, opening the road to the general concept of a topological space that followed shortly.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] During the 1930s Hassler Whitney and others clarified the foundational aspects of the subject, and thus intuitions dating back to the latter half of the 19th century became precise, and developed through differential geometry and Lie group theory.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Notably, the Whitney embedding theorem showed that the intrinsic definition in terms of charts was equivalent to Poincaré's definition in terms of subsets of Euclidean space.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Two-dimensional manifolds, also known as a 2D *surfaces* embedded in our common 3D space, were considered by Riemann under the guise of Riemann surfaces, and rigorously classified in the beginning of the 20th century by Poul Heegaard and Max Dehn.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Poincaré pioneered the study of three-dimensional manifolds and raised a fundamental question about them, today known as the Poincaré conjecture.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] After nearly a century, Grigori Perelman proved the Poincaré conjecture (see the Solution of the Poincaré conjecture).
[src:topology/manifold-p01] William Thurston's geometrization program, formulated in the 1970s, provided a far-reaching extension of the Poincaré conjecture to the general three-dimensional manifolds.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Andrey Markov Jr. showed in 1960 that no algorithm exists for classifying four-dimensional manifolds.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Important work on higher-dimensional manifolds, including analogues of the Poincaré conjecture, had been done earlier by René Thom, John Milnor, Stephen Smale and Sergei Novikov.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A very pervasive and flexible technique underlying much work on the topology of manifolds is Morse theory.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The simplest kind of manifold to define is the *topological manifold*, which looks locally like some "ordinary" Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:topology/manifold-p01] By definition, all manifolds are topological manifolds, so the phrase "topological manifold" is usually used to emphasize that a manifold lacks additional structure, or that only its topological properties are being considered.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Formally, a topological manifold is a topological space locally homeomorphic to a Euclidean space.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This means that every point has a neighbourhood for which there exists a homeomorphism (a bijective continuous function whose inverse is also continuous) mapping that neighbourhood to $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:topology/manifold-p01] These homeomorphisms are the charts of the manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In order to discuss such properties for a manifold, one needs to specify further structure and consider differentiable manifolds and Riemannian manifolds discussed below.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In particular, the same underlying topological manifold can have several mutually incompatible classes of differentiable functions and an infinite number of ways to specify distances and angles.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Usually additional technical assumptions on the topological space are made to exclude pathological cases.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] It is customary to require that the space be Hausdorff and second countable.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The *dimension* of the manifold at a certain point is the dimension of the Euclidean space that the charts at that point map to (number *n* in the definition).
[src:topology/manifold-p01] All points in a connected manifold have the same dimension.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Some authors require that all charts of a topological manifold map to Euclidean spaces of same dimension.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In that case every topological manifold has a topological invariant, its dimension.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] For most applications, a special kind of topological manifold, namely, a *differentiable manifold*, is used.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] If the local charts on a manifold are compatible in a certain sense, one can define directions, tangent spaces, and differentiable functions on that manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In particular it is possible to use calculus on a differentiable manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Each point of an *n*-dimensional differentiable manifold has a tangent space.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This is an *n*-dimensional Euclidean space consisting of the tangent vectors of the curves through the point.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Two important classes of differentiable manifolds are *smooth* and *analytic manifolds*.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] For smooth manifolds the transition maps are smooth, that is, infinitely differentiable.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Analytic manifolds are smooth manifolds with the additional condition that the transition maps are analytic (they can be expressed as power series).
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The sphere can be given analytic structure, as can most familiar curves and surfaces.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A rectifiable set generalizes the idea of a piecewise smooth or rectifiable curve to higher dimensions; however, rectifiable sets are not in general manifolds.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] To measure distances and angles on manifolds, the manifold must be Riemannian.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A *Riemannian manifold* is a differentiable manifold in which each tangent space is equipped with an inner product $\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle$ in a manner which varies smoothly from point to point.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Given two tangent vectors u and v , the inner product $\langle u,v\rangle$ gives a real number.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The dot (or scalar) product is a typical example of an inner product.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This allows one to define various notions such as length, angles, areas (or volumes), curvature and divergence of vector fields.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] All differentiable manifolds (of constant dimension) can be given the structure of a Riemannian manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The Euclidean space itself carries a natural structure of Riemannian manifold (the tangent spaces are naturally identified with the Euclidean space itself and carry the standard scalar product of the space).
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Many familiar curves and surfaces, including for example all *n*-spheres, are specified as subspaces of a Euclidean space and inherit a metric from their embedding in it.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A *Finsler manifold* allows the definition of distance but does not require the concept of angle; it is an analytic manifold in which each tangent space is equipped with a norm, $\|\cdot \|$ , in a manner which varies smoothly from point to point.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This norm can be extended to a metric, defining the length of a curve; but it cannot in general be used to define an inner product.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Any Riemannian manifold is a Finsler manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A Euclidean vector space with the group operation of vector addition is an example of a non-compact Lie group.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A simple example of a compact Lie group is the circle: the group operation is simply rotation.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This group, known as $\operatorname {U} (1)$ , can be also characterised as the group of complex numbers of modulus 1 with multiplication as the group operation.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Other examples of Lie groups include special groups of matrices, which are all subgroups of the general linear group, the group of $n\times n$ matrices with non-zero determinant.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] If the matrix entries are real numbers, this will be an $n^{2}$ -dimensional disconnected manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The orthogonal groups, the symmetry groups of the sphere and hyperspheres, are $n(n-1)/2$ dimensional manifolds, where $n-1$ is the dimension of the sphere.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Further examples can be found in the table of Lie groups.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Different notions of manifolds have different notions of classification and invariant; in this section we focus on smooth closed manifolds.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The classification of smooth closed manifolds is well understood *in principle*, except in dimension 4: in low dimensions (2 and 3) it is geometric, via the uniformization theorem and the solution of the Poincaré conjecture, and in high dimension (5 and above) it is algebraic, via surgery theory.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This is a classification in principle: the general question of whether two smooth manifolds are diffeomorphic is not computable in general.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Further, specific computations remain difficult, and there are many open questions.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Orientable surfaces can be visualized, and their diffeomorphism classes enumerated, by genus.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Given two orientable surfaces, one can determine if they are diffeomorphic by computing their respective genera and comparing: they are diffeomorphic if and only if the genera are equal, so the genus forms a complete set of invariants.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] However, one can determine if two manifolds are *different* if there is some intrinsic characteristic that differentiates them.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] One could hope to develop an arsenal of invariant criteria that would definitively classify all manifolds up to isomorphism.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] It is known that for manifolds of dimension 4 and higher, no program exists that can decide whether two manifolds are diffeomorphic.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Smooth manifolds have a rich set of invariants, coming from point-set topology, classic algebraic topology, and geometric topology.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The most familiar invariants, which are visible for surfaces, are orientability (a normal invariant, also detected by homology) and genus (a homological invariant).
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Smooth closed manifolds have no local invariants (other than dimension), though geometric manifolds have local invariants, notably the curvature of a Riemannian manifold and the torsion of a manifold equipped with an affine connection.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This distinction between local invariants and no local invariants is a common way to distinguish between geometry and topology.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] All invariants of a smooth closed manifold are thus global.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Algebraic topology is a source of a number of important global invariant properties.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Some key criteria include the *simply connected* property and orientability (see below).
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Indeed, several branches of mathematics, such as homology and homotopy theory, and the theory of characteristic classes were founded in order to study invariant properties of manifolds.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In dimensions two and higher, a simple but important invariant criterion is the question of whether a manifold admits a meaningful orientation.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Consider a topological manifold with charts mapping to $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Given an ordered basis for $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , a chart causes its piece of the manifold to itself acquire a sense of ordering, which in 3-dimensions can be viewed as either right-handed or left-handed.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Overlapping charts are not required to agree in their sense of ordering, which gives manifolds an important freedom.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] For some manifolds, like the sphere, charts can be chosen so that overlapping regions agree on their "handedness"; these are *orientable* manifolds.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The latter possibility is easy to overlook, because any closed surface embedded (without self-intersection) in three-dimensional space is orientable.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Some illustrative examples of non-orientable manifolds include: (1) the Möbius strip, which is a manifold with boundary, (2) the Klein bottle, which must intersect itself in its 3-space representation, and (3) the real projective plane, which arises naturally in geometry.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Begin with an infinite circular cylinder standing vertically, a manifold without boundary.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Slice across it high and low to produce two circular boundaries, and the cylindrical strip between them.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This is an orientable manifold with boundary, upon which "surgery" will be performed.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Slice the strip open, so that it could unroll to become a rectangle, but keep a grasp on the cut ends.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Twist one end 180°, making the inner surface face out, and glue the ends back together seamlessly.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] This results in a strip with a permanent half-twist: the Möbius strip.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Its boundary is no longer a pair of circles, but (topologically) a single circle; and what was once its "inside" has merged with its "outside", so that it now has only a *single* side.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Similarly to the Klein Bottle below, this two dimensional surface would need to intersect itself in two dimensions, but can easily be constructed in three or more dimensions.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Take two Möbius strips; each has a single loop as a boundary.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Straighten out those loops into circles, and let the strips distort into cross-caps.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Gluing the circles together will produce a new, closed manifold without boundary, the Klein bottle.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Closing the surface does nothing to improve the lack of orientability, it merely removes the boundary.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Thus, the Klein bottle is a closed surface with no distinction between inside and outside.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In three-dimensional space, a Klein bottle's surface must pass through itself.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Building a Klein bottle which is not self-intersecting requires four or more dimensions of space.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Begin with a sphere centered on the origin.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Every line through the origin pierces the sphere in two opposite points called *antipodes*.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Although there is no way to do so physically, it is possible (by considering a quotient space) to mathematically merge each antipode pair into a single point.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] The closed surface so produced is the real projective plane, yet another non-orientable surface.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] It has a number of equivalent descriptions and constructions, but this route explains its name: all the points on any given line through the origin project to the same "point" on this "plane".
[src:topology/manifold-p01] For two dimensional manifolds a key invariant property is the genus, or "number of handles" present in a surface.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] A torus is a sphere with one handle, a double torus is a sphere with two handles, and so on.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] Indeed, it is possible to fully characterize compact, two-dimensional manifolds on the basis of genus and orientability.
[src:topology/manifold-p01] In higher-dimensional manifolds genus is replaced by the notion of Euler characteristic, and more generally Betti numbers and homology and cohomology.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] Just as there are various types of manifolds, there are various types of maps of manifolds.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] In addition to continuous functions and smooth functions generally, there are maps with special properties.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] In geometric topology a basic type are embeddings, of which knot theory is a central example, and generalizations such as immersions, submersions, covering spaces, and ramified covering spaces.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] Basic results include the Whitney embedding theorem and Whitney immersion theorem.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] In Riemannian geometry, one may ask for maps to preserve the Riemannian metric, leading to notions of isometric embeddings, isometric immersions, and Riemannian submersions; a basic result is the Nash embedding theorem.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] sometimes called regular functions or functionals, by analogy with algebraic geometry or linear algebra.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] These are of interest both in their own right, and to study the underlying manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] This leads to such functions as the spherical harmonics, and to heat kernel methods of studying manifolds, such as hearing the shape of a drum and some proofs of the Atiyah–Singer index theorem.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] The definition of a manifold can be generalized by dropping the requirement of finite dimensionality.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] The singularities correspond to fixed points of the group actions, and the actions must be compatible in a certain sense.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] algebraic varieties over the real or complex numbers are manifolds.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] is glued together from affine algebraic varieties, which are zero sets of polynomials over algebraically closed fields.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] are likewise glued together from affine schemes, which are a generalization of algebraic varieties.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] (top dimensional manifold and codimension 1 boundary) and manifolds with corners (top dimensional manifold, codimension 1 boundary, codimension 2 corners).
[src:topology/manifold-p02] is a topological space formed by gluing disks of different dimensionality together.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] In general the resulting space is singular, hence not a manifold.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] is a space that behaves like a manifold from the point of view of homology theory.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] These are not all manifolds, but (in high dimension) can be analyzed by surgery theory similarly to manifolds, and failure to be a manifold is a local obstruction, as in surgery theory.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] It is an algebra with respect to the pointwise addition and multiplication.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] Suppose also that the following conditions hold.
[src:topology/manifold-p02] for which the above conditions hold, is called a Sikorski differential space.
[src:topology/topological-space] In mathematics, a **topological space** is, roughly speaking, a space in which closeness is defined but cannot necessarily be measured by a numeric distance.
[src:topology/topological-space] More specifically, a topological space is a set whose elements are called points, along with an additional structure called a topology, which can be defined as a set of neighbourhoods for each point that satisfy some axioms formalizing the concept of closeness.
[src:topology/topological-space] There are several equivalent definitions of a topology, the most commonly used of which is the definition through open sets.
[src:topology/topological-space] A topological space is the most general type of a mathematical space that allows for the definition of limits, continuity, and connectedness.
[src:topology/topological-space] Common types of topological spaces include Euclidean spaces, metric spaces and manifolds.
[src:topology/topological-space] Although very general, the concept of topological spaces is fundamental, and used in virtually every branch of modern mathematics.
[src:topology/topological-space] The study of topological spaces in their own right is called general topology (or point-set topology).
[src:topology/topological-space] Around 1735, Leonhard Euler discovered the formula $V-E+F=2$ relating the number of vertices ( V ), edges ( E ) and faces ( F ) of a convex polyhedron, and hence of a planar graph.
[src:topology/topological-space] The study and generalization of this formula, specifically by Cauchy (1789–1857) and L'Huilier (1750–1840), boosted the study of topology.
[src:topology/topological-space] In 1827, Carl Friedrich Gauss published *General investigations of curved surfaces*, which in section 3 defines the curved surface in a similar manner to the modern topological understanding.
[src:topology/topological-space] Yet, "until Riemann's work in the early 1850s, surfaces were always dealt with from a local point of view (as parametric surfaces) and topological issues were never considered".
[src:topology/topological-space] The subject is clearly defined by Felix Klein in his "Erlangen Program" (1872): the geometry invariants of arbitrary continuous transformation, a kind of geometry.
[src:topology/topological-space] The term "topology" was introduced by Johann Benedict Listing in 1847, although he had used the term in correspondence some years earlier instead of previously used "Analysis situs".
[src:topology/topological-space] The foundation of this science, for a space of any dimension, was created by Henri Poincaré.
[src:topology/topological-space] His first article on this topic appeared in 1894.
[src:topology/topological-space] In the 1930s, James Waddell Alexander II and Hassler Whitney first expressed the idea that a surface is a topological space that is locally like a Euclidean plane.
[src:topology/topological-space] Topological spaces were first defined by Felix Hausdorff in 1914 in his seminal "Principles of Set Theory".
[src:topology/topological-space] Metric spaces had been defined earlier in 1906 by Maurice Fréchet, though it was Hausdorff who popularised the term "metric space" (German: *metrischer Raum*).
[src:topology/topological-space] The utility of the concept of a *topology* is shown by the fact that there are several equivalent definitions of this mathematical structure.
[src:topology/topological-space] Thus one chooses the axiomatization suited for the application.
[src:topology/topological-space] The most commonly used is that in terms of *open sets*, but perhaps more intuitive is that in terms of *neighbourhoods* and so this is given first.
[src:topology/topological-space] This axiomatization is due to Felix Hausdorff.
[src:topology/topological-space] The elements of X are usually called *points*, though they can be any mathematical object.
[src:topology/topological-space] Let ${\mathcal {N}}$ be a function assigning to each x (point) in X a non-empty collection ${\mathcal {N}}(x)$ of subsets of $X.$ The elements of ${\mathcal {N}}(x)$ will be called *neighbourhoods* of x with respect to ${\mathcal {N}}$ (or, simply, *neighbourhoods of x*).
[src:topology/topological-space] The function ${\mathcal {N}}$ is called a neighbourhood topology if the axioms below are satisfied; and then X with ${\mathcal {N}}$ is called a **topological space**.
[src:topology/topological-space] The first three axioms for neighbourhoods have a clear meaning.
[src:topology/topological-space] Given such a structure, a subset U of X is defined to be **open** if U is a neighbourhood of all points in $U.$ The open sets then satisfy the axioms given below in the next definition of a topological space.
[src:topology/topological-space] A subset $C\subseteq X$ is said to be *closed* in $(X,\tau )$ if its complement $X\setminus C$ is an open set.
[src:topology/topological-space] Note that from this definition, it follows that the empty set and X are simultaneously open *and* closed – that is, the two sets are complements of one another, while each of them is, itself, open.
[src:topology/topological-space] Given $X=\{1,2,3,4\},$ the discrete topology on X is the power set of $X,$ which is the family $\tau =\wp (X)$ consisting of all possible subsets of $X.$ In this case the topological space $(X,\tau )$ is called a *discrete space*.
[src:topology/topological-space] Given $X=\mathbb {Z} ,$ the set of integers, the family $\tau$ of all finite subsets of the integers plus $\mathbb {Z}$ itself is *not* a topology, because (for example) the union of all finite sets not containing zero is not finite and therefore not a member of the family of finite sets.
[src:topology/topological-space] The intersection of any collection of closed sets is also closed.
[src:topology/topological-space] The union of any finite number of closed sets is also closed.
[src:topology/topological-space] Using these axioms, another way to define a topological space is as a set X together with a collection $\tau$ of closed subsets of $X.$ Thus the sets in the topology $\tau$ are the closed sets, and their complements in X are the open sets.
[src:topology/topological-space] There are many other equivalent ways to define a topological space: in other words the concepts of neighbourhood, or that of open or closed sets can be reconstructed from other starting points and satisfy the correct axioms.
[src:topology/topological-space] A net is a generalisation of the concept of sequence.
[src:topology/topological-space] A topology is completely determined if for every net in X the set of its accumulation points is specified.
[src:topology/topological-space] Many topologies can be defined on a set to form a topological space.
[src:topology/topological-space] The terms *larger* and *smaller* are sometimes used in place of finer and coarser, respectively.
[src:topology/topological-space] The terms *stronger* and *weaker* are also used in the literature, but with little agreement on the meaning, so one should always be sure of an author's convention when reading.
[src:topology/topological-space] A function $f:X\to Y$ between topological spaces is called continuous if for every $x\in X$ and every neighbourhood N of $f(x)$ there is a neighbourhood M of x such that $f(M)\subseteq N.$ This relates easily to the usual definition in analysis.
[src:topology/topological-space] Equivalently, f is continuous if the inverse image of every open set is open.
[src:topology/topological-space] This is an attempt to capture the intuition that there are no "jumps" or "separations" in the function.
[src:topology/topological-space] A homeomorphism is a bijection that is continuous and whose inverse is also continuous.
[src:topology/topological-space] Two spaces are called *homeomorphic* if there exists a homeomorphism between them.
[src:topology/topological-space] From the standpoint of topology, homeomorphic spaces are essentially identical.
[src:topology/topological-space] In category theory, one of the fundamental categories is **Top**, which denotes the category of topological spaces whose objects are topological spaces and whose morphisms are continuous functions.
[src:topology/topological-space] The attempt to classify the objects of this category (up to homeomorphism) by invariants has motivated areas of research, such as homotopy theory, homology theory, and K-theory.
[src:topology/topological-space] A given set may have many different topologies.
[src:topology/topological-space] If a set is given a different topology, it is viewed as a different topological space.
[src:topology/topological-space] Any set can be given the discrete topology in which every subset is open.
[src:topology/topological-space] The only convergent sequences or nets in this topology are those that are eventually constant.
[src:topology/topological-space] Also, any set can be given the trivial topology (also called the indiscrete topology), in which only the empty set and the whole space are open.
[src:topology/topological-space] Every sequence and net in this topology converges to every point of the space.
[src:topology/topological-space] This example shows that in general topological spaces, limits of sequences need not be unique.
[src:topology/topological-space] However, often topological spaces must be Hausdorff spaces where limit points are unique.
[src:topology/topological-space] There exist numerous topologies on any given finite set.
[src:topology/topological-space] Such spaces are called finite topological spaces.
[src:topology/topological-space] Finite spaces are sometimes used to provide examples or counterexamples to conjectures about topological spaces in general.
[src:topology/topological-space] Any set can be given the cofinite topology in which the open sets are the empty set and the sets whose complement is finite.
[src:topology/topological-space] This is the smallest T1 topology on any infinite set.
[src:topology/topological-space] Any set can be given the cocountable topology, in which a set is defined as open if it is either empty or its complement is countable.
[src:topology/topological-space] When the set is uncountable, this topology serves as a counterexample in many situations.
[src:topology/topological-space] The real line can also be given the lower limit topology.
[src:topology/topological-space] Here, the basic open sets are the half open intervals $[a,b).$ This topology on $\mathbb {R}$ is strictly finer than the Euclidean topology defined above; a sequence converges to a point in this topology if and only if it converges from above in the Euclidean topology.
[src:topology/topological-space] This example shows that a set may have many distinct topologies defined on it.
[src:topology/topological-space] Every manifold has a natural topology since it is locally Euclidean.
[src:topology/topological-space] Similarly, every simplex and every simplicial complex inherits a natural topology from .
[src:topology/topological-space] The Sierpiński space is the simplest non-discrete topological space.
[src:topology/topological-space] It has important relations to the theory of computation and semantics.
[src:topology/topological-space] Every subset of a topological space can be given the subspace topology in which the open sets are the intersections of the open sets of the larger space with the subset.
[src:topology/topological-space] For any indexed family of topological spaces, the product can be given the product topology, which is generated by the inverse images of open sets of the factors under the projection mappings.
[src:topology/topological-space] For example, in finite products, a basis for the product topology consists of all products of open sets.
[src:topology/topological-space] For infinite products, there is the additional requirement that in a basic open set, all but finitely many of its projections are the entire space.
[src:topology/topological-space] This construction is a special case of an initial topology.
[src:topology/topological-space] A common example of a quotient topology is when an equivalence relation is defined on the topological space $X.$ The map f is then the natural projection onto the set of equivalence classes.
[src:topology/topological-space] This construction is a special case of a final topology.
[src:topology/topological-space] Metric spaces embody a metric, a precise notion of distance between points.
[src:topology/topological-space] Every metric space can be given a metric topology, in which the basic open sets are open balls defined by the metric.
[src:topology/topological-space] This is the standard topology on any normed vector space.
[src:topology/topological-space] On a finite-dimensional vector space this topology is the same for all norms.
[src:topology/topological-space] There are many ways of defining a topology on $\mathbb {R} ,$ the set of real numbers.
[src:topology/topological-space] The standard topology on $\mathbb {R}$ is generated by the open intervals.
[src:topology/topological-space] The set of all open intervals forms a base or basis for the topology, meaning that every open set is a union of some collection of sets from the base.
[src:topology/topological-space] In particular, this means that a set is open if there exists an open interval of non zero radius about every point in the set.
[src:topology/topological-space] More generally, the Euclidean spaces $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ can be given a topology.
[src:topology/topological-space] In the **usual topology** on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ the basic open sets are the open balls.
[src:topology/topological-space] Similarly, $\mathbb {C} ,$ the set of complex numbers, and $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ have a standard topology in which the basic open sets are open balls.
[src:topology/topological-space] For any algebraic objects we can introduce the discrete topology, under which the algebraic operations are continuous functions.
[src:topology/topological-space] For any such structure that is not finite, we often have a natural topology compatible with the algebraic operations, in the sense that the algebraic operations are still continuous.
[src:topology/topological-space] This leads to concepts such as topological groups, topological rings, topological fields and topological vector spaces over the latter.
[src:topology/topological-space] Local fields are topological fields important in number theory.
[src:topology/topological-space] The Zariski topology is defined algebraically on the spectrum of a ring or an algebraic variety.
[src:topology/topological-space] On $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ or $\mathbb {C} ^{n},$ the closed sets of the Zariski topology are the solution sets of systems of polynomial equations.
[src:topology/topological-space] Many sets of linear operators in functional analysis are endowed with topologies that are defined by specifying when a particular sequence of functions converges to the zero function.
[src:topology/topological-space] A linear graph has a natural topology that generalizes many of the geometric aspects of graphs with vertices and edges.
[src:topology/topological-space] Topological spaces can be broadly classified, up to homeomorphism, by their topological properties.
[src:topology/topological-space] A topological property is a property of spaces that is invariant under homeomorphisms.
[src:topology/topological-space] To prove that two spaces are not homeomorphic it is sufficient to find a topological property not shared by them.
[src:topology/topological-space] Examples of such properties include connectedness, compactness, and various separation axioms.
[src:topology/topological-space] For algebraic invariants see algebraic topology.
[src:topology/topology] A topological space is a set endowed with a structure, called a *topology*, which allows defining continuous deformation of subspaces, and, more generally, all kinds of continuity.
[src:topology/topology] Euclidean spaces, and, more generally, metric spaces are examples of topological spaces, as any distance or metric defines a topology.
[src:topology/topology] The deformations that are considered in topology are homeomorphisms and homotopies.
[src:topology/topology] A property that is invariant under such deformations is a topological property.
[src:topology/topology] The following are basic examples of topological properties: the dimension, which allows distinguishing between a line and a surface; compactness, which allows distinguishing between a line and a circle; connectedness, which allows distinguishing a circle from two non-intersecting circles.
[src:topology/topology] The ideas underlying topology go back to Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, who in the 17th century envisioned the *geometria situs* and *analysis situs*.
[src:topology/topology] Leonhard Euler's Seven Bridges of Königsberg problem and polyhedron formula are arguably the field's first theorems.
[src:topology/topology] The term *topology* was introduced by Johann Benedict Listing in the 19th century, although, it was not until the first decades of the 20th century that the idea of a topological space was developed.
[src:topology/topology] The motivating insight behind topology is that some geometric problems depend not on the exact shape of the objects involved, but rather on the way they are put together.
[src:topology/topology] For example, the square and the circle have many properties in common: they are both one-dimensional objects (from a topological point of view) and both separate the plane into two parts, the part inside and the part outside.
[src:topology/topology] In one of the first papers in topology, Leonhard Euler demonstrated that it was impossible to find a route through the town of Königsberg (now Kaliningrad) that would cross each of its seven bridges exactly once.
[src:topology/topology] This result did not depend on the lengths of the bridges or on their distance from one another, but only on connectivity properties: which bridges connect to which islands or riverbanks.
[src:topology/topology] This Seven Bridges of Königsberg problem led to the branch of mathematics known as graph theory.
[src:topology/topology] As with the *Bridges of Königsberg*, the result does not depend on the shape of the sphere; it applies to any kind of smooth blob, as long as it has no holes.
[src:topology/topology] To deal with these problems that do not rely on the exact shape of the objects, one must be clear about just what properties these problems do rely on.
[src:topology/topology] From this need arises the notion of homeomorphism.
[src:topology/topology] The impossibility of crossing each bridge just once applies to any arrangement of bridges homeomorphic to those in Königsberg, and the hairy ball theorem applies to any space homeomorphic to a sphere.
[src:topology/topology] Intuitively, two spaces are homeomorphic if one can be deformed into the other without cutting or gluing.
[src:topology/topology] A famous example, known as the "Topologist's Breakfast", is that a topologist cannot distinguish a coffee mug from a doughnut.
[src:topology/topology] A pliable torus (shaped like a doughnut) can be reshaped to a coffee mug by creating a dimple and progressively enlarging it while shrinking the central hole into the mug's handle.
[src:topology/topology] Homeomorphism can be considered the most basic topological equivalence.
[src:topology/topology] This is harder to describe without getting technical, but the essential notion is that two objects are homotopy equivalent if they both result from "squishing" some larger object.
[src:topology/topology] Topology, as a well-defined mathematical discipline, originates in the early part of the twentieth century, but some isolated results can be traced back several centuries.
[src:topology/topology] Among these are certain questions in geometry investigated by Leonhard Euler.
[src:topology/topology] His 1736 paper on the Seven Bridges of Königsberg is regarded as one of the first practical applications of topology.
[src:topology/topology] On 14 November 1750, Euler wrote to a friend that he had realized the importance of the *edges* of a polyhedron.
[src:topology/topology] This led to his polyhedron formula, *V* − *E* + *F* = 2 (where V, E, and F respectively indicate the number of vertices, edges, and faces of the polyhedron).
[src:topology/topology] Some authorities regard this analysis as the first theorem, signaling the birth of topology.
[src:topology/topology] Further contributions were made by Augustin-Louis Cauchy, Ludwig Schläfli, Johann Benedict Listing, Bernhard Riemann and Enrico Betti.
[src:topology/topology] Listing introduced the term "Topologie" in *Vorstudien zur Topologie*, written in his native German, in 1847, having used the word for ten years in correspondence before its first appearance in print.
[src:topology/topology] The English form "topology" was used in 1883 in Listing's obituary in the journal *Nature* to distinguish "qualitative geometry from the ordinary geometry in which quantitative relations chiefly are treated".
[src:topology/topology] Their work was corrected, consolidated and greatly extended by Henri Poincaré.
[src:topology/topology] In 1895, he published his ground-breaking paper on *Analysis Situs*, which introduced the concepts now known as homotopy and homology, which are now considered part of algebraic topology.
[src:topology/topology] The development of topology in the 20th century was marked by significant advances in both foundational theory and its application to other fields of mathematics.
[src:topology/topology] Unifying the work on function spaces of Georg Cantor, Vito Volterra, Cesare Arzelà, Jacques Hadamard, Giulio Ascoli and others, Maurice Fréchet introduced the metric space in 1906.
[src:topology/topology] A metric space is now considered a special case of a general topological space, with any given topological space potentially giving rise to many distinct metric spaces.
[src:topology/topology] In 1914, Felix Hausdorff coined the term "topological space" and defined what is now called a Hausdorff space.
[src:topology/topology] Currently, a topological space is a slight generalization of Hausdorff spaces, given in 1922 by Kazimierz Kuratowski.
[src:topology/topology] Modern topology depends strongly on the ideas of set theory, developed by Georg Cantor in the later part of the 19th century.
[src:topology/topology] In addition to establishing the basic ideas of set theory, Cantor considered point sets in Euclidean space as part of his study of Fourier series.
[src:topology/topology] For further developments, see point-set topology and algebraic topology.
[src:topology/topology] The 2022 Abel Prize was awarded to Dennis Sullivan "for his groundbreaking contributions to topology in its broadest sense, and in particular its algebraic, geometric and dynamical aspects".
[src:topology/topology] The term "topology" also refers to a specific mathematical idea central to the area of mathematics called topology.
[src:topology/topology] Informally, a topology describes how elements of a set relate spatially to each other.
[src:topology/topology] The same set can have different topologies.
[src:topology/topology] For instance, the real line, the complex plane, and the Cantor set can be thought of as the same set with different topologies.
[src:topology/topology] Formally, let X be a set and let τ be a family of subsets of X.
[src:topology/topology] Any union of elements of τ is an element of τ.
[src:topology/topology] Any intersection of finitely many elements of τ is an element of τ.
[src:topology/topology] If τ is a topology on X, then the pair (*X*, *τ*) is called a topological space.
[src:topology/topology] The notation *X**τ* may be used to denote a set X endowed with the particular topology τ.
[src:topology/topology] By definition, every topology is a π-system.
[src:topology/topology] The members of τ are called *open sets* in X.
[src:topology/topology] A subset of X is said to be closed if its complement is in τ (that is, its complement is open).
[src:topology/topology] A subset of X may be open, closed, both (a clopen set), or neither.
[src:topology/topology] The empty set and X itself are always both closed and open.
[src:topology/topology] An open subset of X which contains a point x is called an open neighborhood of x.
[src:topology/topology] A function or map from one topological space to another is called *continuous* if the inverse image of any open set is open.
[src:topology/topology] If the function maps the real numbers to the real numbers (both spaces with the standard topology), then this definition of continuous is equivalent to the definition of continuous in calculus.
[src:topology/topology] If a continuous function is one-to-one and onto, and if the inverse of the function is also continuous, then the function is called a homeomorphism and the domain of the function is said to be homeomorphic to the range.
[src:topology/topology] Another way of saying this is that the function has a natural extension to the topology.
[src:topology/topology] If two spaces are homeomorphic, they have identical topological properties and are considered topologically the same.
[src:topology/topology] The cube and the sphere are homeomorphic, as are the coffee cup and the doughnut.
[src:topology/topology] However, the sphere is not homeomorphic to the doughnut.
[src:topology/topology] While topological spaces can be extremely varied and exotic, many areas of topology focus on the more familiar class of spaces known as manifolds.
[src:topology/topology] A *manifold* is a topological space that resembles Euclidean space near each point.
[src:topology/topology] More precisely, each point of an n-dimensional manifold has a neighborhood that is homeomorphic to the Euclidean space of dimension n.
[src:topology/topology] Lines and circles, but not figure eights, are one-dimensional manifolds.
[src:topology/topology] Examples include the plane, the sphere, and the torus, which can all be realized in three dimensions without self-intersection, and the Klein bottle and real projective plane, which cannot.
[src:topology/topology] General topology is the branch of topology dealing with the basic set-theoretic definitions and constructions used in topology.
[src:topology/topology] It is the foundation of most other branches of topology, including differential topology, geometric topology, and algebraic topology.
[src:topology/topology] Another name for general topology is point-set topology.
[src:topology/topology] The basic object of study is topological spaces, which are sets equipped with a topology, that is, a family of subsets, called *open sets*, which is closed under finite intersections and (finite or infinite) unions.
[src:topology/topology] The fundamental concepts of topology, such as *continuity*, *compactness*, and *connectedness*, can be defined in terms of open sets.
[src:topology/topology] Intuitively, continuous functions take nearby points to nearby points.
[src:topology/topology] Compact sets are those that can be covered by finitely many sets of arbitrarily small size.
[src:topology/topology] Connected sets are sets that cannot be divided into two pieces that are far apart.
[src:topology/topology] The words *nearby*, *arbitrarily small*, and *far apart* can all be made precise by using open sets.
[src:topology/topology] Several topologies can be defined on a given set.
[src:topology/topology] Changing a topology consists of changing the collection of open sets.
[src:topology/topology] This changes which functions are continuous and which subsets are compact or connected.
[src:topology/topology] Metric spaces are an important class of topological spaces where the distance between any two points is defined by a function called a *metric*.
[src:topology/topology] In a metric space, an open set is a union of open disks, where an open disk of radius r centered at x is the set of all points whose distance to x is less than r.
[src:topology/topology] Many common spaces are topological spaces whose topology can be defined by a metric.
[src:topology/topology] This is the case of the real line, the complex plane, real and complex normed vector spaces and Euclidean spaces.
[src:topology/topology] Algebraic topology is a branch of mathematics that uses tools from algebra to study topological spaces.
[src:topology/topology] The basic goal is to find algebraic invariants that classify topological spaces up to homeomorphism, or more commonly up to homotopy equivalence.
[src:topology/topology] The most important of these invariants are homotopy groups, homology, and cohomology.
[src:topology/topology] Although algebraic topology primarily uses algebra to study topological problems, using topology to solve algebraic problems is sometimes also possible.
[src:topology/topology] Algebraic topology, for example, allows for a convenient proof that any subgroup of a free group is again a free group.
[src:topology/topology] Differential topology is the field dealing with differentiable functions on differentiable manifolds.
[src:topology/topology] It is closely related to differential geometry and together they make up the geometric theory of differentiable manifolds.
[src:topology/topology] More specifically, differential topology considers the properties and structures that require only a smooth structure on a manifold to be defined.
[src:topology/topology] Smooth manifolds are "softer" than manifolds with extra geometric structures, which can act as obstructions to certain types of equivalences and deformations that exist in differential topology.
[src:topology/topology] For instance, volume and Riemannian curvature are invariants that can distinguish different geometric structures on the same smooth manifold – that is, one can smoothly "flatten out" certain manifolds, but it might require distorting the space and affecting the curvature or volume.
[src:topology/topology] Geometric topology is a branch of topology that primarily focuses on low-dimensional manifolds (that is, spaces of dimensions 2, 3, and 4) and their interaction with geometry, but it also includes some higher-dimensional topology.
[src:topology/topology] Some examples of topics in geometric topology are orientability, handle decompositions, local flatness, crumpling and the planar and higher-dimensional Schönflies theorem.
[src:topology/topology] In high-dimensional topology, characteristic classes are a basic invariant, and surgery theory is a key theory.
[src:topology/topology] Occasionally, one needs to use the tools of topology but a "set of points" is not available.
[src:topology/topology] In pointless topology one considers instead the lattice of open sets as the basic notion of the theory, while Grothendieck topologies are structures defined on arbitrary categories that allow the definition of sheaves on those categories and with that the definition of general cohomology theories.
[src:topology/topology] Topology has been used to study various biological systems including molecules and nanostructures (e.g., membraneous objects); this application led to both molecular topology and molecular nanotopology.
[src:topology/topology] Furthermore, circuit topology and knot theory have been extensively applied to classify and compare the topology of folded proteins and nucleic acids.
[src:topology/topology] Circuit topology classifies folded molecular chains based on the pairwise arrangement of their intra-chain contacts and chain crossings.
[src:topology/topology] Knot theory, a branch of topology, is used in biology to study the effects of certain enzymes on DNA.
[src:topology/topology] These enzymes cut, twist, and reconnect the DNA, causing knotting with observable effects such as slower electrophoresis.
[src:topology/topology] Topological data analysis uses techniques from algebraic topology to determine the large-scale structure of a set (for instance, determining if a cloud of points is spherical or toroidal).
[src:topology/topology] Analyse these topological complexes via algebraic topology – specifically, via the theory of persistent homology.
[src:topology/topology] Encode the persistent homology of a data set in the form of a parameterized version of a Betti number, which is called a barcode.
[src:topology/topology] Several branches of programming language semantics, such as domain theory, are formalized using topology.
[src:topology/topology] In this context, Steve Vickers, building on work by Samson Abramsky and Michael B.
[src:topology/topology] Smyth, characterizes topological spaces as Boolean or Heyting algebras over open sets, which are characterized as semidecidable (equivalently, finitely observable) properties.
[src:topology/topology] Topology is relevant to physics in areas such as condensed matter physics, quantum field theory, quantum computing and physical cosmology.
[src:topology/topology] The topological dependence of mechanical properties in solids is of interest in the disciplines of mechanical engineering and materials science.
[src:topology/topology] Electrical and mechanical properties depend on the arrangement and network structures of molecules and elementary units in materials.
[src:topology/topology] The compressive strength of crumpled topologies is studied in attempts to understand the high strength to weight of such structures that are mostly empty space.
[src:topology/topology] Topology is of further significance in Contact mechanics where the dependence of stiffness and friction on the dimensionality of surface structures is the subject of interest with applications in multi-body physics.
[src:topology/topology] A topological quantum field theory (or topological field theory or TQFT) is a quantum field theory that computes topological invariants.
[src:topology/topology] Although TQFTs were invented by physicists, they are also of mathematical interest, being related to, among other things, knot theory, the theory of four-manifolds in algebraic topology, and the theory of moduli spaces in algebraic geometry.
[src:topology/topology] Donaldson, Jones, Witten, and Kontsevich have all won Fields Medals for work related to topological field theory.
[src:topology/topology] The topological classification of Calabi–Yau manifolds has important implications in string theory, as different manifolds can sustain different kinds of strings.
[src:topology/topology] In topological quantum computers, the qubits are stored in topological properties, that are by definition invariant with respect to homotopies.
[src:topology/topology] In cosmology, topology can be used to describe the overall shape of the universe.
[src:topology/topology] This area of research is commonly known as spacetime topology.
[src:topology/topology] In condensed matter, a relevant application to topological physics comes from the possibility of obtaining a one-way current, which is a current protected from backscattering.
[src:topology/topology] It was first discovered in electronics with the famous quantum Hall effect, and then generalized in other areas of physics, for instance in photonics.
[src:topology/topology] David Thouless, Duncan Haldane, and Michael Kosterlitz were awarded the 2016 Nobel Prize in Physics for their work on Topological orders.
[src:topology/topology] The possible positions of a robot can be described by a manifold called configuration space.
[src:topology/topology] In the area of motion planning, one finds paths between two points in configuration space.
[src:topology/topology] These paths represent a motion of the robot's joints and other parts into the desired pose.
[src:topology/topology] Disentanglement puzzles are based on topological aspects of the puzzle's shapes and components.
[src:topology/topology] In order to create a continuous join of pieces in a modular construction, it is necessary to create an unbroken path in an order that surrounds each piece and traverses each edge only once.
[src:topology/topology] This process is an application of the Eulerian path.
